<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 92 / Money Markets: Optimism on UK rate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAUTIOUS optimism that European interest rates will be cut has dominated
money markets all week, and this was the note on which trading closed
yesterday, writes James Blitz.
There is now a clear expectation in the sterling market that UK base rates
will be cut in conjunction with Thursday's autumn statement. Dealers only
differ over the scale of the cut. Some argue that it will be as small as
1/2 a percentage point, and others, more daringly, punt on a 2 per cent fall
in base rates.
Whatever the differences, the optimistic mood brought 3-month money down
3/8 per cent on the week to a close of 7 5/16 per cent offered yesterday.
The December short sterling contract closed 20 base points up from last
Friday's close, at 93.54 yesterday. This prices 3-month money in December at
around 6 1/2 per cent, a level compatible with 6 per cent base rates.
The downward trend in money market rates is almost certain to continue in
the early part of next week. One commercial bank dealer expected 3-month
money to be at around 7 1/8 per cent, or even 7 per cent, by Wednesday.
In the French and German markets, too, there is a growing feeling that rates
will be cut soon.
The 25 basis point cut in the French intervention rate on Monday gave an
upward boost to French cash rates and futures all week. Three-month money
closed at 9 5/16 per cent offered yesterday, some  3/8 per cent down on the
week.
The December franc contract reached a high of 91.00 yesterday, some 20 basis
points up from Tuesday's opening level.
But, the French markets are expecting rates to come down slowly because of
the currency's membership of the European Exchange Rate Mechanism.
Yesterday's close for the December contract prices is only 25 basis points
off the intervention rate this year. Dealers will be watching the Bank of
France's repurchase operations on Monday and Thursday for official movement.
The French market's caution is explained by the Bundesbank's recent
statements.
The German central bank has hinted strongly that it will be watching how the
German government targets the budget deficit and the public sector pay round
in the next few weeks, before cutting the discount rate.
</TEXT>
