<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 92 / International Company News: Woolworth eyes German disposal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WOOLWORTH, the US retailer, announced yesterday that it was considering
selling much of its important German operations, comprising more than 500
stores with annual turnover of more than Dollars 1.6bn.
The potential disposal does not include the company's expanding Foot Locker
business, selling athletic shoes, which it is building up as a major chain
across Europe.
Woolworth has had a significant presence in Germany for decades and the
country provides about one sixth of the group's total sales of Dollars 10bn.
Profits boomed following the reunification, with revenues leaping from
Dollars 1.18bn in 1989 to Dollars 1.66bn in 1990 and operating profits
soaring from Dollars 80m to Dollars 154m. However, in 1991 profits slipped
to Dollars 127m on revenues little changed.
The company said yesterday it was exploring various alternatives for its
general merchandise and specialty stores in Germany, including the possible
disposal of some or all of the operations to one or more third parties.
A spokeswoman would only say the company had the enhancement of shareholder
value as one of its strategic objectives.
Analysts said the disposal would free funds and allow Woolworth to
concentrate on its European strategy for Foot Locker, which is now the
company's most important single business in the US. The company has 134 Foot
Locker stores in seven European countries, including 27 outlets in Germany,
and wants to increase that to 1,000 outlets by the year 2000.
German operations which could be sold comprise more than 320 Woolworth
general stores and more than 180 specialty stores, including Rubin costume
jewellery, handbags and accessory shops; Moderna and Der Schuh shoe stores;
and Lady Plus clothes stores for larger-sized women.
The company is being advised by US investment banks Merrill Lynch and
Salomon Brothers. Woolworth shares rose Dollars  3/8 on the news to close at
Dollars 33 7/8 on the New York Stock Exchange.
Earlier this week Woolworth reported sharply improved third-quarter results,
with after-tax profits rising to Dollars 65m from Dollars 41m a year ago.
Sales rose 2.5 per cent to Dollars 2.5bn.
However, the company has disappointed Wall Street over the past two years as
Foot Locker in the US has grown into a mature business, while its two other
big American divisions - the Woolworth general merchandise chain and Kinney
family shoe - have been shrinking.
</TEXT>
