<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 92 / EOC rebuffed in part-timers case: Appeal court curtails
legal role of commission
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EQUAL Opportunities Commission has no right to bring judicial review
proceedings against the government, the Court of Appeal ruled yesterday. Mr
Alan Lakin, legal adviser to the commission, said: 'This severely undermines
our position.'
The court said the commission - which has a statutory duty to enforce the
law and to promote equal opportunities - should concentrate on assisting
individual women to take cases through the industrial tribunal system, and
play an 'advisory' role to government.
The statement is a blow to the commission's strategy of mounting legal
challenges on issues which it believes affect large numbers of women.
The Appeal Court's statement came in a ruling, by a 2-1 majority, upholding
a High Court decision to reject a challenge by the commission to the
government over the rights of part-time workers - 90 per cent of whom are
women.
The EOC argued that the government was failing to comply with European
Community obligations to protect part-timers from less favourable treatment
than full-timers, particularly in relation to redundancy and unfair
dismissal.
Lord Justice Kennedy and Lord Justice Hirst agreed the challenge had not
been properly brought. Lord Justice Dillon disagreed, saying he would have
granted a declaration that the UK was in breach of Treaty of Rome
obligations and European law by providing less favourable treatment of
part-time employees working between eight and 16 hours a week.
The judges unanimously rejected the commission's claim that the criteria for
the calculation of redundancy pay discriminated against part-timers. The
commission was refused permission to renew its challenge in the House of
Lords. It is considering whether to appeal to the Lords directly.
The ruling means that, under national law, an employee working fewer than
eight hours a week remains ineligible for redundancy pay or unfair dismissal
compensation.
A full-time employee working 16 or more hours a week qualifies for
redundancy pay and compensation for unfair dismissal after two years of
continuous employment, while someone working between eight and 16 hours
takes five years to qualify.
Part-timers who have previously worked full-time are not given any credit
for periods of full-time work when their payments are calculated.
The commission failed to persuade the appeal court to intervene on the
grounds that all of this was contrary to Article 119 of the Treaty of Rome,
which lays down equal treatment for men and women at work, and the EC's
directives on equal pay and equal treatment.
The commission said the majority decision that the organisation had no legal
right to seek judicial review in this type of case was 'disturbing'.
Mr Lakin said: 'The commission believes its duty is to act on behalf of this
group of women by preventing them from having to go through lengthy,
expensive and stressful proceedings.'
The commission believes judicial review is the most efficient use of its
small legal budget of about Pounds 600,000 a year.
Last year it used judicial review proceedings to establish that women
serving in the armed forces may not be sacked for becoming pregnant.
The Department of Employment said: 'We have always argued that these
regulations are necessary to preserve job opportunities for women and to
minimise the burden on business.'
</TEXT>
