   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNOR Bill Clinton yesterday made his first move since winning the US
presidential election on Tuesday by naming Mr Vernon Jordan and Mr Warren
Christopher to head the transition team managing the formation of his new
administration.
Mr Jordan, a lawyer, civil rights leader and former head of the National
Urban League, will chair the transition team, with Mr Christopher, who
served as deputy secretary of state in the Carter administration, in charge
of day-to-day operations.
Both men helped Mr Clinton with the selection of Senator Al Gore as his
vice-presidential running mate, and their appointment to lead the transition
team, in preference to some more overtly political aides such as Mr Mickey
Kantor, chairman of the Clinton campaign, is viewed as a signal that the
president-elect aims to take a pragmatic, issue-oriented approach to
governing.
Mr Christopher said the first priority was to set up an orderly process for
the selection of Mr Clinton's cabinet, which will take office following his
inauguration on January 20 next year.
He expected economic policy posts to be the first filled, reflecting the
initial priority of the new administration. Consideration would also be
given to forming an economic council similar to the existing National
Security Council.
Mr Clinton, who spent yesterday nursing his ailing voice and continuing his
telephone conversations with world leaders, has said he plans a 'laser'
concentration on the economy.
Senator George Mitchell, leader of the Democratic majority in the Senate,
added yesterday that he expected an economic programme in the first 100 days
of the new administration.
Mr Christopher, who has been suggested as a possible secretary of state or
attorney general, said he assumed his role in the appointment of the
government would rule him out for any prominent post in the future
administration.
He said he would not assume the same exclusion for other members of the
team, which will include Mr Kantor, Mr Henry Cisneros, former mayor of San
Antonio, former governor Madeleine Kunin of Vermont, and Mr Mack McLarty,
chairman of the Arkansas-Louisiana Gas Company.
</TEXT>
