<HEADLINE>
FT  07 NOV 92 / Scent of blood on campus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHOULD he ever seek the French presidency, as it is rumoured he might, Mr
Jacques Delors, beleaguered president of the European Commission, was given
a dry run in presidential treatment yesterday.
Mobbed by television cameramen and crowds of students alternately jeering
and cheering, the hapless Mr Delors was almost physically carried into the
London School of Economics where he delivered the first Jean Monnet lecture.
Security services were a little sparse and Mr Delors must have wished for
the muscular presence of truncheon-wielding French CRS policemen to knock a
few heads together and clear his path. In the event, he was dumped
breathless, but still remarkably composed and good-humoured, on the podium.
It was not, of course, Mr Delors' learned expose of the history of monetary
co-operation that the scribes and picture- takers had turned up to hear.
They had smelled blood.
Mr Delors' visit to the LSE followed the reported allegation by Mr Ray
MacSharry, the EC's chief trade negotiator, that his boss had sabotaged an
agreement with the US to protect the interests of French farmers and, by
implication, his own ambitions for the French presidency.
Appetites were whetted even before the famous man's arrival by whispered
information from a harassed academic. The Foreign Office, he indicated, had
just telephoned to speak to Mr Delors. At the moment Mr Delors was about
leave for lunch with the LSE's director, it was divulged that Mr John Major
had summoned 'monsieur le president' to Downing Street.
The dry academic atmosphere positively crackled with electricity. The LSE's
political scientists are not often given such a taste of realpolitik.
On the substance of the row over Gatt, Mr Delors' tormenters went away
unsatisfied. Lost in a forest of microphones and pushing journalists, he was
heard to protest that he never interfered in the negotiations conducted by
Mr MacSharry.
'I give my advice, but afterwards, if the majority of the Commission do not
share my advice, I express my full solidarity with the commissioner in
charge of negotiating.'
Would he resign? Mr Delors looked bewildered. ' Why? I am in good health,'
he answered.
In Dublin, a tired-looking Mr MacSharry arrived for a quiet weekend at home
in the west of Ireland. Unfortunately his arrival coincided with the opening
day of an election campaign.
Long thought of as a candidate for the premiership and leadership of the
Fianna Fail party, a post could be up for grabs if Mr Albert Reynolds, the
prime minister, fails to win a majority in the election.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
