<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Speculation on realignment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPECULATION that another realignment of the European exchange rate mechanism
could take place before the end of the year dominated trading yesterday,
pushing the higher-yielding ERM currencies down against the D-Mark, writes
James Blitz.
Although tensions inside the ERM have eased considerably since the crisis of
early autumn, a shadow has continued to hang over the weaker currencies in
the system, the Spanish peseta, Portuguese escudo and Irish punt.
All three currencies remain close to their ERM floors against the D-Mark,
while dealers have continued to question whether their current rates are
competitive enough against the strengthened German currency.
Although German money market rates are coming down, there are fears that the
Bundesbank will not ease rates as quickly as the markets anticipate, keeping
interest rates in those countries with weaker European currencies
unsustainably high.
Yesterday Mr Helmut Schlesinger underlined the degree of restraint in
Bundesbank policy by saying that most countries had budget deficits that
were too big, and that the Maastricht criterion that deficits should be 3
per cent of GDP should be narrowed.
Speculation about new ERM parities was fuelled by a newspaper interview with
Mr Carlos Solchaga, the Spanish finance minister, in which he said a further
realignment in the ERM would probably be needed before the end of the year
to restore stability. 'We are absolutely open to all changes of parities,'
he said. Later in the day, Ireland announced that it would be lifting all
its remaining exchange controls by the end of this year.
Both moves may suggest that pressure is being put on Germany to agree to a
realignment in tandem with the cut in official rates that is anticipated by
the end of the year.
The Italian lira's strong performance against the D-Mark has also led to
speculation that it could re-enter the ERM at the same time as a
realignment. The lira yesterday closed at L854.6 per D-Mark, some 15 per
cent above its September low.
Mr Solchaga's comments, and their implications for German rates, were cited
as one reason why the dollar rose to DM1.5845 yesterday, its highest level
since the historic low was reached on September 2. The dollar later ended in
London at DM1.5785, up around a pfennig on the day. In New York it finished
higher at DM1.5830.
Speculation on German rates also helped sterling. The currency was boosted
by the UK government's narrow victory in the vote on European union in the
House of Commons, but later fell back to close at DM2.4275, down  3/4
pfennig on balance.
However, the D-Mark appreciated against the weaker ERM currencies. The
peseta slipped to a close of Pta71.58 from a previous Pta71.17.
</TEXT>
