<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Special situations enliven
mixed day's trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANY significant movements were restricted to special situations yesterday as
most bourses closed mixed, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT was lifted by short-covering, and an earnings upgrade for the
steel and engineering group, Preussag. The DAX index ended 8.24 higher at
1,480.93 as turnover rose from DM3.6bn to DM4.2bn.
Deutsche Bank Research said that after Wednesday's analysts' meeting at
Preussag, it had revised its EPS forecast from DM27.50 to DM31 a share for
1991/92 and from DM25 to DM27.50 for 1992/93. This followed an earlier,
downward revision by the broker three or four weeks ago.
Preussag jumped DM9.50 to DM324.00 for a cumulative gain of DM20.50 this
week. The group has reduced its dependence on steel and engineering with
other divisions, particularly in telecommunications, which have been doing
considerably better than some people expected.
Mannesmann rose DM4 to DM204.80, and hit DM206 after hours in London on an
unlikely story that British Telecom might take it over. Analysts pooh-poohed
the story.
PARIS moved in a fairly narrow range after the rise earlier in the week took
the CAC-40 index above the 1,800 level. The CAC-40 index ended little
changed at 1,804.70, up 0.63. Turnover stood at FFr2.37bn, of which FFr1.7bn
was generated by CAC-40 stocks.
Rhone-Poulenc CIs rose FFr25 or 5 per cent to FFr527 on bargain-hunting
after their recent fall, linked to the fall in shares in its unit, Institut
Merieux International. There were also rumours that the non-voting CIs were
being supported by state-controlled institutions to enable the French
government to price its planned partial privatisation of Rhone-Poulenc at
FFr535-FFr540 for each new voting share.
Carrefour rose FFr15 to FFr2,410 in reasonable volume of 31,090 shares
following a positive meeting with some analysts.
MILAN ended lower as operators started to close their positions ahead of the
close of the account next week. The Comit index fell 9.09 to 429.49 as
turnover continued to drop back after the recent high levels. Turnover
yesterday was estimated at around Wednesday's L186bn.
In its latest market report, Kleinwort Benson recommends selling into
strength since it believes that the market's performance in the last month
has more than discounted the recent fall in interest rates and the recently
acquired government credibility. It adds that fundamentals remain negative.
Fiat slipped L107 to L4,441. After the close, car industry data showed that
Fiat's share of the domestic market fell to 43.8 per cent in October, down
from 46.2 per cent in October 1991.
BRUSSELS saw the food retailer, Delhaize, fall BFr120 or 7 per cent to
BFr1,585 in heavy volume of 152,900 shares. Dealers blamed the drop on a
fall in the shares of its US unit, Food Lion, ahead of the showing of an
unflattering film, shot secretly at Food Lion, on the ABC television channel
yesterday evening. Delhaize was also hit by news that unions in Belgium
might stage strikes in December in support of non-unionised Food Lion
employees. The Bel-20 index dropped 9.77 to 1,146.15.
AMSTERDAM closed mixed as more gloomy corporate news hit the market. The CBS
Tendency index closed at 102.6, up 0.3.
Philips dropped Fl 1.70 or 8.9 per cent to Fl 17.40 after announcing a
third-quarter loss of Fl 154m, following the release of its third-quarter
earnings. Its music and video recording subsidiary PolyGram shed 50 cents to
Fl 44.70.
KLM picked up 40 cents to Fl 22.50 after it announced a 12 per cent net
profit decline in its fiscal second quarter to Fl 170.1m.
Akzo added another Fl 2.10 to Fl 133.70 in the wake of its
better-than-expected third-quarter results announced earlier in the week.
ZURICH extended its rally to a fifth day as the higher dollar encouraged
domestic and foreign investors. In spite of profit-taking, the SMI index
ended another 10.0 higher at 1,951.5.
OSLO inched up 0.19 to 346.29, flattened by lower oil prices although the
stronger dollar lifted the shipping index by 5.30 to 317.68, and the
state-backed rescue for Elkem, the troubled metals group, left the latter's
A shares NKr3.50 higher at NKr17.50.
