<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equities advance in higher volume
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RELIEF THAT both the presidential election in the US and the Maastricht
debate in the UK are now over and done with brought the buyers back into the
London stock market yesterday. Gains in the dollar stocks were restrained by
Wall Street's reluctance so far to make a definite response to President
Clinton's success at the polls.
But firmness in domestic issues signalled the stock market's belief that,
now that its Maastricht proposals have won parliamentary support, Mr John
Major's Conservative government will introduce measures to restimulate the
UK economy. A batch of significant corporate developments also helped the
equity market.
The FT-SE Index gained 19.4 to 2,711.1. But the market made a slow start,
dipping 10.3 in early trading as London shied away from the near 30-point
fall overnight in New York's Dow Average.
Share prices rallied quickly, however, when the stock index futures opened
for business, and although trading volume was light at first, the Footsie
had climbed by more than 21 points by midsession.
London faltered a little in the afternoon and increased turnover towards the
close indicated that some investors had taken the opportunity to cash in on
the morning's profits. The New York stock market made another sluggish start
but brightened later, to show a gain of 7.56 on the Dow as London closed for
business.
Strategists appear to have divided into two groups; those who have
confidence in prospects for the re-stimulation of the economies of the
leading industrial nations, and those who fear that the UK stock market has
been overbought and could be due for a sharp correction. The two groups
showed their hands yesterday in conflicting strategies in the equity and
stock index futures markets.
Among the international stocks, oil shares steadied from the depression
caused by fears that President Clinton may tighten environmental
requirements. However, there was only a mild response to trading results
from British Petroleum. Attention was focused on the telecommunications
sector by the news that BT (British Telecommunications) will sell its 22 per
cent stake in McCaw Cellular Communications, of the US. Traders immediately
began to seek a new target for BT in the cellular phone market.
A firm dollar helped many overseas earning stocks. BAT Industries, which
reported profits this week, came in for renewed speculative support, and ICI
regained more of the ground lost over the past fortnight.
But the multi-national drug stocks lagged behind the market as worries over
the new US President's likely policies towards medical funding resurfaced.
Glaxo, the front-runner of the sector, rallied in late dealings, however, as
London grew more hopeful regarding the outlook on Wall Street.
Among domestic stocks, there were gains in the retail and store sectors,
which continued to look for early cuts in UK base rates. Banking shares also
found buyers again after trading uneasily over the past few trading
sessions.
In late dealings, the stock market's hopes for recovery in the domestic
economy were encouraged by the disclosure that UK car sales rose by 8 per
cent in October, the first sign of hope from a struggling industry.
</TEXT>
