<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Ex-director moves to oust Hoskins chairman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DENNIS Bailey, a former non-executive director of Hoskins Brewery, the
Leicester-based real ale brewer, will today call on shareholders to support
moves to oust Mr Barrie Hoar, the company's chairman, and his brother, Mr
Robert Hoar, from the board.
Resolutions to remove the brothers have been tabled for an extraordinary
meeting on November 18.
Mr Richard Cattermole, chairman of Ryan Elizabeth, a pubs and hotels
operator, and a Hoskins shareholder, and his associate, Mr Jeremy Lea, are
seeking election in their place.
In a letter to shareholders today, Mr Bailey, who has an 8 per cent stake in
the company, says: 'If the resolutions fall, I fear that our investment will
be at further risk and the share price may fall again.'
Hoskins' profits record and lack of dividends had demonstrated that the Hoar
brothers had not been competent managers, Mr Bailey says. 'It is time for
change.'
In his letter, Mr Bailey says Mr Barrie Hoar was 'running Hoskins as if it
were a family business and not a public company'.
He adds that 'a misleading and false impression' of his own role at Hoskins
was given by Mr Hoar in a letter to shareholders last month.
He denies taking any active part in deals involving the acquisition of
Netherton Ales, and of Tatlocks, a catering company, both of which resulted
in losses, or of proposing the acquisition of Edencorp Leisure, now in
compulsory liquidation. In each case, Hoskins had been independently
advised, Mr Bailey says.
'It is in my view fair to say that in reality most decisions, both major and
minor, affecting Hoskins appear to be made by Mr Barrie Hoar and Mr Robert
Hoar,' he adds.
Mr Bailey says he resigned from Hoskins a year ago after a series of
differences with the Hoar brothers over their business conduct.
</TEXT>
