<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / International Company News: Public outcry fails to fend off
bid for BNZ - The pain caused by Australia's takeover of a neighbour's
financial icon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY HALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Australia Bank (NAB) yesterday emerged triumphant in its NZDollars
1.5bn (USDollars 787m) battle to buy the Bank of New Zealand (BNZ), marking
the end of the most bitter and controversial takeover in New Zealand's
history.
NAB announced last night it had secured 90.27 per cent of the ordinary
shares, a day ahead of the final deadline. This narrow victory, just 0.27
per cent over the threshold allowing it to acquire the remaining shares
compulsorily, ends a chapter in the turbulent history of the country's
biggest bank. To the last, minority shareholders in BNZ battled to keep the
bank in local hands.
All week several shareholders staged pickets outside bank branches, seeking
to stop the sale. Thousands of other small shareholders sought to halt the
deal by refusing to accept NAB's 80 cents a share offer.
Two US funds, the Wisconsin Investment Board and Grantham Mayo van Otterloo,
with a combined 3 per cent holding in BNZ, encouraged the protesters by
saying they were unlikely to accept the offer.
Controversy over the sale of BNZ was inflamed by Mr Winston Peters, an MP in
the a ruling National party. Armed with documents tabled under parliamentary
privilege, he alleged wrong-doing by BNZ directors and others involved with
the bank from 1988 to 1990.
Letters to newspapers, callers to radio talk shows and public opinion polls
suggested a majority of New Zealanders wanted an inquiry into the bank which
the National Party government is refusing to allow, despite a pre-election
promise to do so.
Most critics said they did not want BNZ sold, while others expressed concern
that the sale would see the country's banking dominated by four Australian
banks - ANZ, Westpac, NAB and Commonwealth - and two British banks -
Countrywide and National Westminster. Only one bank remains in New Zealand
hands, Trust Bank, a grouping of regional banks effectively excluded from
the main Auckland market.
An often acrimonious extraordinary meeting, forced by dissident shareholders
last Friday, showed the depth of feeling among the 1,500 shareholders able
to attend the marathon five-and-a-half hour meeting. Many targetted their
frustration at director Sir Michael Fay, a representative of Fay, Richwhite,
and Ms Ruth Richardson, the finance minister. It was their decision in June
to sell their combined 82.9 per cent holding to the NAB that sparked the
uproar.
However, the BNZ has been no stranger to controversy in the past. Launched
by Auckland entrepreneurs in 1860, there were early accusations of
impropriety in land deals.
In the late 1880s, BNZ was involved in property and other speculation,
requiring a rescue with the injection of taxpayers' money. Oddly the same
thing happened 100 years later.
But successive governments maintained a share in the bank until it was
nationalised by the Labour government in 1946. In 1986, a reformist Labour
government sold 17 per cent to the public for NZDollars 1.75 a share.
The shareholders who bought these shares spearheaded the latest campaign to
keep the bank in local hands, arguing that improving profits showed it was
on a road to recovery.
Small shareholders have had two shocks recently: one in 1989 when BNZ
revealed heavy losses following the 1987 crash. However, the bigger one came
in September 1990, when the bank was forced to raise NZDollars 1.5bn from
the government, Fay, Richwhite and other sources to cover large unexpected
losses in Australia.
Last week's extraordinary meeting revealed for the first time how grave the
Australian problems had been. As part of the 1990 rescue, BNZ set up Adbro,
a separate company to handle the 'bad bank' loan portfolio, while BNZ itself
became a 'good bank' and continued to trade.
About half the bad and doubtful debts in Adbro, which has a total of
NZDollars 2.7bn in debts, will never be recovered.
The Adbro issue dominated the extraordinary meeting, as a leading group of
dissidents argued that NAB's offer of 80 cents a share was artificially
depressed by overly conservative accounting of the potential recoveries from
Adbro.
Mr Paul Kocourek of Booz Allen and Hamilton, the international management
consultancy, revealed how much of the financial crisis in September 1990 was
due to the BNZ's ill-judged foray into Australia between 1985 and 1988, when
it sought to become a leading player there.
He said that much of 77 per cent of increased provisioning needed between
March and September 1990 was due to problem Australian loans, which
accounted for only 20 per cent of the bank's lending.
Mr Kocourek said hardly anyone had seen the magnitude of Australia
recession, while hopes for an improvement in the New Zealand economy did not
materialise. This meant an increasing number of companies were unable to
repay interest and principal on their loans.
'Not only did more loans go bad, but the value of the collateral
underpinning them deteriorated substantially,' he said. Property prices in
Sydney and Melbourne fell by an average 40 to 50 per cent.
He said that, while the board could be criticised, very few commentators
expected the collapse in Australia to be so severe. Only a year earlier
independent valuers had been forecasting a maximum 5 per cent drop in
property values.
The provisioning in September 1990 forecast recoveries at NZDollars 1.07bn,
or 40 per cent of the debts that were put into Adbro. Since then, the bank
had recovered NZDollars 622.4m, about 58 per cent of the expected recovery
level. Mr Kocourek said further recoveries in Adbro are forecast at
NZDollars 456m.
Responding to suggestions that the bad debt provisions were too high, which
suggested that the BNZ was being sold too cheaply, he said there could be no
certainty about the provisioning levels, but his judgment was that they
fairly reflected the value of the bad loan portfolio.
He said that, of the total bad debt recoveries, 60 per cent would come from
Australia and 40 per cent from New Zealand. Provisioning was based on the
expectation of only modest economic growth over the next several years, and
could change if the Australian and New Zealand economies became 'Asian
Tigers'.
NAB's determination not to pay more than 80 cents a share, or to offer a
share swap, did not ease the way for it to buy the BNZ. Nor did it lessen
the controversy over the loss of a national institution, popularly called
the 'peoples' bank' to Australian control.
Most New Zealanders harbour deep-seated suspicions about their bigger
neighbour, and clashes both on and off the sporting field are legendary.
Now that it has succeeded in its takeover, NAB will need to mount a big
public relations effort. It has said it intends to keep BNZ's name and
identity, emphasising that it will allow BNZ the same measure of autonomy
they permit the banks it controls in Britain and Northern Ireland.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 30
</PAGE>
