<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / International Company News: Citizen plunges 26% with outlook
bleak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CITIZEN, the leading Japanese watch and electronics manufacturer, yesterday
warned that the Japanese business environment would become increasingly
severe in the second half of this fiscal year after reporting a 26.7 per
cent fall in pre-tax profits in the six months to September.
Citizen said that despite the Japanese government's emergency spending
package announced in August, the company was planning for increasingly harsh
business conditions in the second half.
The company said it expected sluggish consumer demand and industrial
investment in Japan would be compounded by slow growth in export markets in
Europe and the US. This partly reflected the recent rise in the value of the
yen which has undermined the competitiveness of Japanese exports.
Citizen, which makes industrial machinery, personal computers and portable
televisions as well as watches, reported a 25.6 per cent fall in operating
profits to Y5.8bn (Dollars 47m) in the six months to September compared with
the same period last year.
Pre-tax profits fell 26.7 per cent to Y7.5bn on a 1.6 per cent increase in
sales to Y123.8bn. Net income per share was 7.8 per cent down at Y14.7 but
the company maintained its interim dividend at Y4.
Citizen's business divisions reported widely differing results. The watch
division, which accounts for about half the company's turnover, fell from
Y62.6bn in the first half of last year to Y62bn this year. Sales of luxury
watches were particularly badly hit which reduced the average price per unit
sold.
Sales of industrial machinery such as computer numerically controlled
machine tools fell by 40.8 per cent to Y9bn.
Information equipment sales were 21 per cent up, largely thanks to Citizen's
miniaturised notebook computers and higher floppy disk drive sales. This
offset a decline in computer printer sales in Europe and north America.
Electronics equipment revenues rose by 23 per cent to Y17.3bn largely as a
result of increased sales of liquid crystal displays and portable colour
televisions.
