</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW World Development, the Hong Kong-based property development to hotels
group, announced a 102 per cent leap in net profit to HKDollars 2.36bn
(USDollars 305.3m) in the year to June 1992, up from HKDollars 1.17bn the
year before.
Around HKDollars 1bn in earnings came from sales of office and residential
properties, and HKDollars 1.4bn from rental income on its property
portfolio.
New World has been one of the more aggressive investors in southern China,
building up a sizeable land bank for development, in addition to its
construction of the Guanzhou northern ring road, a toll road linking Huizhou
with the border city of Shenzhen and two power plants in Zhujiang.
'The outlook for overall economic development in China is particularly
bright. There exists a crying need for industrialisation, land development
and infrastructure in the Mainland,' said Mr Henry Cheng, managing director.
New World also owns the Ramada hotel chain, which manages 101 hotels
worldwide. Hotels continued to suffer from the worldwide recession, but
properties in Hong Kong and China are beginning to see improvements.
The company holds 47.5 per cent of Asia Television, the colony's second TV
channel; Mr Cheng said the outlook was more encouraging, but significant
losses are still being incurred.
A final dividend of 47 cents has been recommended, making a full-year payout
of 68 cents - a 36 per cent increase.
