   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TATA Iron and Steel (Tisco), India's largest private-sector company,
yesterday reported a sharp fall in half-year net profits to Rs502.2m
(Dollars 17.6m) from Rs1.04bn, despite a 28 per cent rise in sales.
Mr Russi Mody, chairman, attributed the poor results to 'steep cost
escalations outside the company's control' and the impact of the sharp
devaluation of the rupee.
Sales advanced to Rs15.37bn from a revised Rs12bn for the same period of
1991, despite the recession in the Indian steel industry.
The news of lower profits depressed company's share price 14 per cent to
Rs266 a share, and was part of the reason for the fall in the Indian stock
market yesterday.
Mr Modi said inflation had meant higher labour costs and substantial
increases in railway freight, power and petroleum prices.
Imported raw materials had become more costly due to the 22 per cent
devaluation of the rupee. Mr Modi, did not give any full-year projections.
The group plans a Rs30bn expansion and diversification programme, to be
completed by 1994, to raise production capacity from 2m tonnes to over 2.7m
tonnes. It also plans to commission two power plants, thermal and
diesel-operated, to augment inadequate power supply.
Tisco's performance in the coming years will depend on its ability to
maintain supplies of raw materials like iron ore and coal from captive
sources, and capacity utilisation.
With the decontrol of steel since January this year, the company will be
better placed to choose the most profitable product mix.
