will reduce second-half operating profit.
News yesterday of the dividend downgrade, from 12 cents to 6 cents a share,
continued the crisis which has dogged the bank since it shocked financial
markets in May with a ADollars 2.32bn (USDollars 1.65bn) pre-tax loss for
the March half.
This forced the bank into a ADollars 1.2bn share issue which was heavily
undersubscribed, culminating in the resignation in October of five Westpac
directors. The prospectus for that share issue made the 12 cents-a-share
final dividend forecast which has now been revised.
Yesterday's downgrade also claimed yet another Westpac executive, with Mr
Anthony Walton, chief general manager with responsibility for the Americas
and Europe, offering his resignation. Westpac said yesterday Mr Walton had
informed the board he had relied on 'assurances from his senior management
that all tax matters had or were being addressed'. He also said 'if the
board wished, he would offer to leave'.
'The board has asked Mr Walton to continue in his executive position into
the first quarter of 1993 to work out an orderly transition. It has also
accepted his resignation as a director and acknowledged his outstanding
contribution to the bank.'
Westpac directors said they regretted that the final dividend rate
previously forecast was no longer possible.
'The tax charge (which is still subject to final audit) follows recognition
of a liability for additional US income taxes and related penalties and
interest of the order of ADollars 115m related to third party interest rate
and currency swap contracts and forward currency contracts assigned
between's Westpac's New York branch and certain non-US branches in 1991 and
1992,' they said.
'The value of potential tax benefit carried forward that could partly offset
the ADollars 115m liability is ADollars 40m. This would only be realised to
the extent that profits would be recorded on future interbranch
transactions. The extent, if any, to which this deduction would be realised
cannot be predicted.'
Westpac said the underlying performance of the bank had remained steady in
the September half. Operating profit after tax was 'in line with earlier
expectations' even though it 'absorbed further write-downs in the value of
listed shares and adverse movement in the actuarial value of staff
superannuation fund surpluses'.
</TEXT>
