<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / International Company News: PWA shares plunge on Canadian
airline strife
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES of PWA Corporation, holding company of Canadian Airlines
International, lost a quarter of their value in early trading yesterday amid
signs that the fight for survival between Canada's two main airlines is
nearing a climax.
PWA's share price plunged as low as CDollars 1.20 from CDollars 1.63 on the
Toronto stock exchange following reports that the embattled company may have
little choice but to file for protection from its creditors.
Air Canada, PWA's arch-rival, this week rejected terms for a merger between
the two airlines. Although a merged carrier would have a virtual monopoly on
domestic routes, it would have an unmanageable debt load of close to
CDollars 8bn (USDollars 6.4bn).
Air Canada's investment advisers, RBC Dominion Securities and Bunting
Warburg, advised it against the deal.
Air Canada said yesterday that 'we would still be interested in a merger,
but on different terms'. The spokesman said, however, that discussions had
not been resumed.
As part of its desperate rescue search, PWA renewed talks this week for an
alliance with American Airlines of Dallas. Such a deal would include
American becoming a big minority shareholder in Canadian Airlines, possibly
in partnership with a group of PWA employees.
Airline sources said that another option open to PWA was to raise cash and
shrink its business by selling its valuable international routes, notably
those across the Pacific, to Air Canada.
Mr Rhys Eaton, PWA's chairman, said he hoped to resolve the company's future
by mid-month. Meanwhile, the board of Continental Airlines, the bankrupt US
carrier, meets today to choose between the bids from two groups of
prospective buyers, one led by Air Canada. Continental is expected to
announce its decision in New York on Monday.
The Canadian airline industry's troubles have taken a heavy toll on PWA and
Air Canada shareholders. PWA shares traded at a peak of CDollars 29.50 in
1987, shortly before the company over-extended itself by buying the charter
airline Wardair.
Air Canada shares changed hands yesterday at CDollars 2.90, a fraction of
the CDollars 12 price at which they were issued to the public when it was
privatised in mid-1989.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 30
</PAGE>
