<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / International Company News: Philips hit by decline in
consumer electronics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   EINDHOVEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE DOWNTURN in the consumer electronics industry pushed Philips, the Dutch
electronics group, into a loss of more than Fl 150m (Dollars 88m) in the
third quarter, prompting the company to consider making restructuring
provisions that are likely to depress full-year results.
The company's shares fell heavily on the news, closing down Fl 1.70 at Fl
17.40
Philips, which has gradually scaled back its 1992 forecast over recent
months, said it could no longer make a profit prediction because it does not
yet know the size of the provisions it will need to take in the key consumer
electronics and components divisions. Until now, Philips had said net
profits from normal business operations would be about half the previous
year's Fl 981m.
The company also said that it would not be paying an interim dividend,
though it declined to comment on a possible final dividend. Philips has not
paid a dividend for two years.
Results in the quarter swung into a net loss of Fl 154m from a net profit of
Fl 188m in 1991, reflecting the continued difficulties besetting the
consumer electronics division and the knock-on effects for the components
division, which makes the group's television tubes. The downturn also hurt
associated companies such as Grundig of Germany and MEC, Philips' components
joint venture with Matsushita of Japan.
Mr Henk Appelo, finance director, said that business areas unrelated to
consumer electronics, such as lighting and professional products, put in a
better performance than a year ago. 'This is evidence to me that Operation
Centurion is working,' he said, referring to the wide-ranging restructuring
campaign unveiled two years ago by Philips' president, Mr Jan Timmer.
Mr Appelo said he was confident that Philips would produce a profit in the
fourth quarter, when results are traditionally stronger because of Christmas
sales of consumer products and end-of-year purchases of capital goods.
Philips would be taking 'clear and tough' measures in consumer electronics
and components and examining the future of loss-making areas of these
businesses. But Mr Appelo repeated earlier company statements that Philips
had no plans to sell entire divisions or to withdraw from consumer
electronics.
'Our problem is an industry-wide problem with which we are grappling, just
as other manufacturers are,' he said.
In the first nine months, net profit from normal business operations
totalled Fl 102m against Fl 510m a year earlier. This figure would have been
Fl 850m higher if it had not been for the consumer electronics-related
businesses. Other areas produced a Fl 400m improvement so far this year.
Mr Appelo said price erosion in consumer electronics had 'stabilised' at 3
per cent in the third quarter. Group turnover in the first nine months fell
by 3 per cent to Fl 38.5bn.
</TEXT>
