<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Hanson/RHM
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Hanson's decision to pull out of the bidding for RHM leaves it in the
awkward position of appearing definitively to have lost that magic touch
with hostile deals. But its choice was not enviable. The agreed offer from
Tomkins is certainly full. Had Hanson topped it, it would have been hard
pressed to justify the price on commercial grounds. RHM's brands are
lacklustre and Tomkins itself, as the likely acquirer, may find it has
bitten off an indigestible morsel in milling and baking.
RHM's ability to exact a price higher than that originally offered by Hanson
is not a particular commendation of its rather feeble defence. It owes more
to the fact that conglomerates still feel the need to scrabble around for
the occasional deal, even though real opportunities are remarkably thin on
the ground.
</TEXT>
