<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / The Lex Column: News Corporation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Still hemmed in on all side by the banks, Mr Rupert Murdoch is clearly
determined to make the best of what he has got. Squeezing a 35 per cent
increase in first-quarter profits from UK newspapers during an advertising
recession is impressive work, even allowing for the benefit of lower
newsprint costs.
The lack of an obvious buyer for the group's remaining weak performers -
such as Ansett - must be all the more frustrating for that. Equally, Fox
films remains a wild card, since its contribution turns on its ability to
produce blockbuster movies on the scale of last year's Home Alone. With no
clear sign of recovery and some drag on earnings, News Corp will find the
heady pace of earnings growth difficult to maintain.
By raising Dollars 1.5bn in equity and long-term debt since the year end,
though, Mr Murdoch has tilted the balance of power away from the banks. His
eagerness to gain an investment grade credit rating suggests more bond
issues to pay off bank debt. High interest costs will rule out anything
ambitious for the time being, but News Corp will at least have a free hand
to invest in its main businesses without the bankers' rubber-stamp. On the
evidence of yesterday's figures this will be freedom enough to keep
shareholders sweet.
</TEXT>
