<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / The Lex Column: BT hangs up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BT can breathe a huge sigh of relief that its investment in McCaw Cellular
has been placed without gallons of red ink. McCaw increasingly looked like a
cul-de-sac for BT, so it must also be satisfying that AT&amp;T's strategic
thirst prompted it to pay twice the market price for BT's stake. Yet, McCaw
has cost BT money once financing costs are factored in.
The sale has also resurrected fears about BT's international strategy.
Constrained by the regulator at home, the company has looked overseas for
growth opportunities. But having set its face against minority participation
in foreign privatisations, it is not clear where the large-scale
opportunities lie. Nor is the company's wish to participate in the growing
UK cable television and entertainment market likely to be granted in the
near future. Even the purchase of the remaining 40 per cent of Cellnet or
development of its systems integration business would not give BT a new
strategic direction.
With many of the avenues for expansion blocked, investors may start to focus
on BT's cash generation. Privatised with a strong balance sheet, the company
has lower gearing than most telecom companies. Indeed, with the proceeds of
the McCaw stake and a strong cash inflow from operations, BT may have net
cash within three years. Shareholders may put it under increasing pressure
to brave the wrath of the regulator and return more of the cash, rather than
sit on a pile or embark on another uncertain foreign adventure.
</TEXT>
