<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / UK Company News: High-Point tumbles Pounds 3.2m into the red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEAN MARSHALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXCEPTIONALS, including restructuring and redundancy costs, pushed
High-Point, the international construction consultancy and management group,
into pre-tax losses of Pounds 3.18m for the year to May 31. Profits in the
previous year amounted to Pounds 1.74m.
The share price tumbled from 150p to 98p.
Mr Ian Reeves, chairman, had warned at the interim stage, when the company
slipped into losses of Pounds 64,000, of the deterioration in the general
business climate.
He said yesterday that conditions had worsened in the second half.
Accordingly, the company had undertaken a review of project work in progress
and debtors in circumstances where clients had suspended or delayed further
works or shown signs of liquidity problems.
Also included in the review were clients in countries where political and
economic changes meant the company was unable to secure prompt payment.
Substantial provisions had accordingly been taken and were included in the
Pounds 1.92m exceptional charge.
Turnover declined to Pounds 55.6m (Pounds 58.7m) and operating profits fell
from Pounds 4.28m to Pounds 1.04m. Interest charges were reduced from Pounds
2.54m to Pounds 2.33m and Mr Reeve reiterated the company's plan to sell
certain businesses in order to reduce debt and reposition the group.
Looking ahead, he expected conditions in the current year to remain
difficult and said the group would continue to overhaul structure and costs.
Although rationalisation costs continued to affect the current half he
expected improved operating profits for the year.
Losses per share came through at 53.5p (earnings 24.4p). The final dividend
is omitted (4.95p) leaving the total at 1.3p (7.5p).
Rationalisation costs were affecting the current half but improved operating
profits were expected for the year
</TEXT>
