<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Sugar goes ahead with plan to take Amstrad private
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ALAN SUGAR, chairman and founder of Amstrad, the computer and satellite
equipment manufacturer, yesterday formally proposed to take the company
private again by buying back the 64 per cent of shares that he does not own
at 30p per share.
The Pounds 112.7m needed to fund the buy-out would be funnelled through
Amshold, a new holding company chaired by Mr Sugar. The money would come as
follows: Mr Sugar, a Pounds 19.5m loan; Amstrad, a Pounds 50m loan; and
Lloyds Bank, a Pounds 43.2m advance.
The share price is less than half the 80p at which he sold a 7.5 per cent
stake in the company in March 1991 to institutional investors. Amstrad
shares closed 1p up at 29p.
The announcement was greeted by the group's institutional investors with a
mixture of suspicion and resignation.
'There is always a lot of suspicion when listed companies are taken private
by their management,' said one investor who voiced concern that Amstrad did
not have any independent non-executive directors on its board.
Mr Sugar said yesterday that shareholders were unlikely to receive a better
deal. Since his preliminary announcement in September, there has been no
other bid on offer.
'The sceptics think that I am being opportunistic and trying to get
something for nothing,' Mr Sugar said.
But 'there is a lot of necessary action that has to be taken with regard to
Amstrad'.
Whether shareholders agreed to the buy-out or not, Amstrad would have to
shrink, which meant small profits for an unforeseeable future.
In response to criticism that he was buying back shares at a much lower
price than he had sold them last year, he said shareholders saw strong rises
in Amstrad shares immediately after he sold shares in 1983, 1985 and 1987.
'On balance the winners have been the shareholders,' he said.
In a letter to shareholders Mr Sugar admitted Amstrad's mistakes. It had not
been able to come up with a hit product to follow its highly popular
low-priced personal computer.
At the same time, as the company grew on the strength of its success, it had
failed to adopt a coherent international strategy and management structures
and systems appropriate to its size.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9236</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8AEAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / AT&amp;T plugs into a new market: Martin Dickson explains why
the industry giant wants to spend Dollars 3.8bn for a 33% stake in the
largest cellular telephone company in the US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'The communications market is a boiling sea of change,' declared Mr Robert
Allen, the undemonstrative chairman of American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, in a
recent speech. On Wednesday he added a tidal wave of his own with the
announcement that AT&amp;T is negotiating to spend Dollars 3.8bn (Pounds 2.3bn)
on a 33 per cent stake in McCaw Cellular Communications, the largest
cellular telephone company in the US.
Part of the stake would come from the purchase of British Telecom's 22 per
cent stake in McCaw for Dollars 1.8bn.
The proposed deal, likely to be sealed in the first half of next year, would
also give AT&amp;T the option of eventually taking voting control of McCaw, a
Seattle-based company which has grown rapidly from humble origins, thanks to
the entrepreneurial spirit and vision of its chairman, the youthful Mr Craig
McCaw.
If the alliance goes ahead it will represent a dramatic plunge by AT&amp;T, the
largest long-distance telecommunications company in the US, into the rapidly
growing cellular telephone market, and will bring it for the first time into
competition with the so-called 'Baby Bells'.
These seven regional telephone companies, which are major players in the
cellular sector, were spun off from AT&amp;T in 1984 when AT&amp;T, affectionately
known as 'Ma Bell', was dismembered in an anti-trust court settlement. The
rump of AT&amp;T was left to fight it out against competition in the
long-distance and international markets and equipment manufacturing. The
Baby Bells, with their local monopolies, were barred by the courts from
entering the long-distance, information or manufacturing businesses.
However, over the past eight years, this neat structure has been gradually
eroding, thanks to technological, competitive and political change.
The emergence of wireless communication, and cellular in particular, has
started to reduce the effectiveness of the Baby Bells' monopoly of local
telephone wires. So too has the growth of entrepreneurial companies using
new fibre optic circuits to link local business customers directly to
long-distance providers.
The Baby Bells, for their part, have been trying to get the 1984
restrictions on their activities removed, but so far have only succeeded in
parts of the information services industry.
The McCaw deal would erode the wobbly structure even further. 'This is a
major, major move in terms of the destabilisation that is going on,' says Mr
Victor Schnee of New Jersey-based Probe Research.
As such it could run into opposition from the Baby Bells, even though Mr
Allen insists there are no legal or regulatory impediments to a deal going
through. 'Is this a wireless approach to putting the Bell system back
together again?' asks Mr Al Boschulte, head of cellular operations at Nynex,
one of the seven babies.
The Modified Final Judgment, the court agreement which broke up the old
AT&amp;T, does not prevent AT&amp;T going into the local telecommunications
business, as long as it does not buy assets of the Baby Bells. Nor does the
Federal Communications Commission, which oversees the industry, seem likely
to object to any transfer of licences involved.
Opponents could try to raise anti-trust objections with the Justice
Department, either on the grounds that this is an alliance between the two
leading service providers in their respective markets, or because AT&amp;T,
which invented cellular technology, is a leading supplier of cellular
equipment. The laissez-faire Bush administration might give these arguments
short shrift. But the anti-trust policies of the incoming Clinton team are
not known.
An alternative tactic for the Baby Bells might be to use the McCaw deal as
ammunition before the courts and in Congress for them to be allowed to enter
the long-distance and equipment manufacturing businesses.
Whatever the upshot, analysts regard the AT&amp;T-McCaw pact as favourable for
both parties. Wireless communications is the fastest-growing area of the US
telecommunication industry, expand-ing at a rate of 30 to 40 per cent a
year, in spite of the recession.
The sector was established in the early 1980s as a patchwork of local
licensees and has been consolidating ever since. McCaw has been one of the
most aggressive acquirers, driven by its chairman's vision of creating a
'seamless national wireless network' to allow cellular subscribers to
communicate easily with other parties anywhere in the US.
Mr McCaw has long argued that the wireless revolution will eventually allow
individuals to have their own portable personal, telecommunications numbers,
allowing phone, fax, video and handwritten communications wherever they are.
AT&amp;T evidently shares this view.
The proposed alliance will give them a strong position to advance this
revolution and profit by it. For McCaw, which has been financially stretched
by takeovers, the deal means being able to reduce its heavy debt burden,
while getting access to AT&amp;T's research and marketing resources and a
long-term licence to use the AT&amp;T name.
For AT&amp;T, the deal means not just a stake in a fast-growing company, but
should also boost its own revenues, with additional traffic being directed
into its long-distance network.
This could spell trouble for its biggest rival in the long-distance market,
MCI Communications, which ironically sold its cellular interests to McCaw in
1986.
Sprint, the third largest long-distance carrier, also sold its cellular
interests in the 1980s, but is now trying to get back into the market
through a Dollars 2.8bn takeover of Centel, an independent Chicago-based
local telephone company which is also the 10th largest cellular provider.
That deal, like the AT&amp;T one, underlines the rapid blurring of America's
telecoms boundaries.
McCaw results, Page 30
