<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Observer: Biting back
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
What a rotten week for Thatcherites. Besides watching the UK government edge
through Britain's commitment to moving towards economic and monetary union,
they've seen the US elect a president promising fiscal stimulus to speed
recovery.
But none of it daunts Sir Alan Walters, Lady Thatcher's ex-adviser and still
an arch-exponent of her economic philosophy, who was in biting mood at a
lunch hosted by market analysts IDEA.
Airing his expectation of British moves to rejoin the exchange rate
mechanism after France's elections next spring, he said re-entry would
probably again be made at the wrong rate 'and we'll be back on that
roller-coaster at the most unpropitious moment of the economic cycle'.
As for Bill Clinton, 'I don't know what lies behind that pretty face. But
whatever it is, it certainly hasn't come out yet.'
He added that his fear is that the new president leans towards protectionism
which, in Walters's view, is now the most worrying feature of the world
economy. 'There really are shades of 1931 in the air, and Mr Clinton has
only one saving grace: a great capacity for learning.'
</TEXT>
