FT  06 NOV 92 / Letter: 'Comprehensive' economists table excludes most
accurate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Prof R E ROWTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, It is very surprising that in the evaluation of economic forecasters
contained in the Financial Times (October 30) no mention whatsoever is made
of Prof Wynne Godley. This evaluation is described as 'the most
comprehensive effort since the recession started to rank economists
according to the accuracy of their growth projections'.
Your tabulation puts the actual change in GDP at -2.4 per cent in 1991 and
 0.9 per cent in 1992, making -3.3 per cent in all. In a survey of forecasts
published in the FT on May 7 1991, Prof Godley's forecasts were almost
exactly right, being -2.7 per cent for 1991 followed by -0.9 per cent for
1992, making -3.6 per cent in total.
All the other forecasts, without exception, covered by your assessment show
an increase in GDP in 1992 and in the two years 1991 and 1992 combined. I
find it mystifying that Peter Marsh should remark in his commentary:
'Although even the top-ranked forecasters were some way out in their
projections, the analysis provides insights into who was on the right
track.'
Instead of being completely ignored, Wynne Godley should be put at the head
of the list. I realise that your survey covers forecasters in operation
regularly since the beginning of 1990. This arbitrary criterion excludes
Prof Godley because his articulated forecasts have been published regularly
only since the beginning of 1991. But this is no excuse for ignoring Godley
when, as the author of your survey must know, his forecasts have been so
much better than those you do include and praise.
Bob Rowthorn,
faculty of economics
and politics,
University of Cambridge,
Austin Robinson Building,
Sidgwick Avenue,
Cambridge CB3 9DD
</TEXT>
