FT  06 NOV 92 / Technology: Neural networks track Footsie - Worth Watching
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Artificial neural networks, comprising layers of interconnected neurons,
have become a unique tool for processing complex financial data because they
can be 'trained' to recognise patterns and discover relationships within
them.
Now Barclays de Zoete Wedd Investment Management, working with University
College, London, has developed a prototype stock forecasting system using
neural technology.
Its accuracy at forecasting the FT-SE 100 share index (the Footsie) is
typically above 80 per cent, reaching 93 per cent on a number of occasions.
This compares with about 50 per cent accuracy for traditional forecasting
methods.
BZW's team, headed by Frank McGroarty, has spent two years with Professor
Philip Treleaven and Siew-Lan Loo of UCL's computer science department to
optimise the neural network specifically for the Footsie. A prototype system
has been installed at BZWIM. Professor Treleaven: UK, 071 380 7288.
</TEXT>
