<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Technology: Driving down a different road - As the final
race approaches, John Griffiths explains why Formula One offers few lessons
for the car industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When Britain's Nigel Mansell starts practice in Adelaide today for the final
round of the 1992 grand prix world championship, it will be his last session
at the wheel of his Canon-sponsored Williams-Renault FW14B  - a car which he
describes as so technologically advanced that, after further improvements
this winter, 'even a puppet will be able to drive it'.
Considering that he has been the beneficiary of most of this technology in
his successful pursuit of this year's world championship, many see his
remark as yet another graceless parting shot at Alain Prost, the French
former world champion who will replace him on the Williams team next season.
Technologically, says Mansell, 'Formula One is going into the space age'.
The Williams-Renault car has a mass of on-board, computer-controlled systems
such as active suspension, a fully automatic gearbox programmed not to let
its driver blow up the engine, and a traction control system to provide
maximum acceleration off the grid and out of corners. It is technical
sophistication to match advanced aerospace technology.
'It takes tens of millions of dollars to get where I've just left in Formula
One and I think that's totally wrong,' says Mansell, who next year will race
a different class of car in North America.
Mansell may believe that the technology race is bad for grand prix as a
sport, but Renault, Honda, Fiat-owned Ferrari, Yamaha, Goodyear and the
other manufacturers of road-going cars, engines, tyres and other equipment
feel differently.
They justify their involvement largely on the grounds that technology
pioneered on Formula One cars cascades down into road cars, to the benefit
of ordinary users in terms of performance, safety or efficiency.
Over the years it has been a persuasive argument. Disc brakes, for example,
evolved from racing. Ordinary motorists owe a debt to grand prix for the
synthetic rubber compounds which provide their tyres with levels of grip,
handling and durability which would have seemed unattainable 20 years ago.
But just how much of the Formula One racing technology now being undertaken
is relevant to the roadgoing vehicle industry is increasingly open to
question.
Even the fuel multinationals which pump large sums of money into grand prix
have had difficulty justifying the relevance of 'witch's brew' fuels for
grand prix cars. These fuels provide as much as 60 or 70 extra horsepower
but some are so lethal that protective suits have had to be worn by people
fuelling the cars.
Fisa, the world governing body of motor sport, is banning the fuels. But oil
group Elf Aquitaine is taking legal action in a bid to get the ban reversed.
That such fuels are widely accepted as costing up to Pounds 100 a litre -
roughly Pounds 25,000 per fill-up - is indicative of how far financial
considerations are put aside.
Some technology is even flowing the other way - out of road cars and into
grand prix. Next season, Prost at Williams will be using anti-lock brakes
for the first time, despite the fact that such ABS systems have been used on
road cars for much of a decade.
The problems of using ABS on a grand prix car are complex because the system
has to deal with the huge weight/speed differentials of a vehicle which has
so much aerodynamic force that it could theoretically run upside down across
a ceiling at more than 130 miles per hour.
The remoteness of grand prix from the mainstream vehicle industry is at
least partially responsible for keeping some of the world's leading
manufacturers out of Formula One.
Jacques Calvet, Peugeot Group's chairman, explains: 'I would prefer to find
a championship which is closer to ordinary cars than grand prix racing. We
like to accept challenges which improve our road cars - like rallying and
sports cars.'
Indeed, so dynamically capable have grand prix cars become - when thay
accelerate, stop and corner they produce forces of up to five times gravity
 -that some of the technology is being reversed. Next year the cars will use
rear tyres that are three inches narrower, for example, in an attempt to
increase braking distances and give more scope to driver ability.
It is also becoming a moot point whether, against the background of world
recession, the businesses which fund the grand prix teams - such as Philip
Morris through its Marlboro brand - and which have no vested stake in motor
industry technology will continue footing the bill when they could compete
with lower-technology cars at a fraction of the grand prix price.
It is this factor which, Fisa president Max Mosley believes, may soon lead
to the wilder technology flights of Formula One being reined in.
'In the long term, it is not realistic to expect a sponsor to pay for
electronic suspension,' he said. 'The only people who would pay for that are
the motor industry, and only if it's useful to them. If we don't stop
spending money on things that are completely useless, sooner or later we'll
go out of business.'
Mosley's concern, however, is not just with financial practicalities in
terms of technology. He believes that over the next decade motor sport is
going to come under increasing attack from environmentalists and that grand
prix will have to pay more attention to areas like emissions  - currently
not even on the agenda - if it is to escape censure. Even then, he
acknowledges, there is the problem of carbon dioxide, the greenhouse gas
which is an inescapable product of combustion.
Financial pressures are such, however, that the technology-limiting process
may already be under way. At a meeting just before the Japanese grand prix a
fortnight ago, members of the Formula One Constructors Association listened
to proposals for an engine speed limit, and for electronic control systems
to be confined to ignition and fuel systems.
Costs and the environment have already been cited by Honda as reasons for
leaving Formula One and scaling down motor sport involvement. Mazda is
withdrawing from the Le Mans 24-hour race next year - which it won in 1991,
the first time by a Japanese manufacturer - and is cutting back other racing
activities in favour of participating with more production-based cars.
Such thinking lies behind the motor sport strategies of General Motors, the
world's largest vehicle maker, which eschews Formula One as being too remote
from its mainstream business.
Mike Nicholson, GM motor sport executive, suggests that the supposed
technical spin-offs are questionable even lower down the motor sport ladder.
'Feedback from the competition programme into the road car, via the rapid
and innovative technological developments needed to remain truly competitive
and reliable, is often cited as justification for motor sport. It was,
without doubt, a very important factor years ago,' he says.
'But the modern car is such a well-developed and refined machine as it comes
off the production line that there is now less-relevant feedback. This
justification, therefore, loses its validity to a large extent. This is
particularly so at the higher levels of the sport where the cars are so
highly developed that it is at times difficult to relate these to their road
car origins.'
The most telling indication that image and politics play a more significant
role than commercially relevant technology was evident at the Japanese grand
prix.
Honda, exiting from grand prix this season, built specially powerful engines
for the race in order to put on a good show for the home crowd. But Renault
had anticipated Honda's move and built its own super-fast engines in order
to prevent Honda obtaining even pole position. In terms of 'usable'
technology, neither manufacturer's practice engines would have lasted the
race.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
