<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Leading Article: Mr Clinton's long haul
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SLOW recovery may have won Mr Clinton the presidency. But it is not the
main economic problem that he will face. To his credit, Mr Clinton has
recognised that it is the long-term performance of the US economy which most
needs improvement. What he has not yet done is make clear to the American
people how painful the choices they face will turn out to be.
Under Mr Bush, the US economy grew at less than 1 per cent a year, far below
the rate of growth of 3 per cent recorded during the Reagan years. As a
result, real income per person stagnated between Mr Bush's election in 1998
and his rejection this week. Yet this is only a part of the sad story of Mr
Bush. As Mr James Annable noted in the FT on October 19, after deducting
elements of consumption that contribute little or nothing to well being,
consumption per person grew by 10 per cent in the first Reagan term and by 9
per cent in the second. Under Mr Bush, by contrast, such 'feel good'
consumption declined by more than 2 per cent.
The irony is that poor Mr Bush bore little responsibility for the discomfort
of the American people. The underlying cause of the stagnation was the way
in which the Reagan years had superimposed debt-financed consumption upon a
slow rate of underlying economic growth.
Between mid-1973 and mid-1992 real income per head in the US rose by a
little over a quarter. It has taken the US these 19 years to achieve an
improvement in overall living standards previously managed in eight.
Moreover, income per head has declined for a significant proportion of the
population because of growing inequality.
What is more, aggregate consumption grew by 30 per cent in real terms during
the Reagan years, while total GDP rose by about a quarter. The difference
was partly explained by a reduced investment rate, down from almost 17 per
cent of GDP in 1980 to 16 per cent in 1988. It was also explained by
increased borrowing from abroad, this being the consequence of the increased
borrowing by both the government and of many individuals and firms. But
under Mr Bush private borrowing virtually stopped, the inevitable result
being a sharp decline in the overall rate of economic growth.
The increased indebtedness of the 1980s was a grievous fault and grievously
has Mr Bush now answered it. But it is also a story of the past. The private
sector balance sheet adjustment is occurring, albeit slowly, and the US
economy is also recovering. The 2.7 per cent annualised increase in GDP in
the third quarter may flatter the underlying trend, but it shows the US is
not in a deep recession. Mr Clinton does not need to put much of his effort
into 'jump-starting' the US economy.
What is far more important is the rate of growth of the economy in the long
term. This depends not on fiddling with aggregate demand, but on the growth
of the capital stock, both physical and human. The people of the US will get
richer only if they save more and learn more.
The gross savings rate in the US has declined from 17 per cent in 1980 to
less than 12 per cent in the first half of 1992. Two percentage points of
the decline can be explained by lower private savings. The big change,
however, is an increase in the rate at which savings are being absorbed by
government, from just over 1 per cent of GDP in 1980 to just under 5 per
cent in 1992. No less important is the quality of US education for the
bottom half of the ability range. Yet just as the 'dissaving' by government
can only be remedied by a combination of cuts in spending and higher taxes,
so reform in education and training demands equally painful structural
reforms.
Mr Clinton has rightly focused on the problem of long-term economic
performance, not just on the immediate malaise. The US needs more saving,
higher skills and a willingness to meet the best the international
competition has to offer. What Mr Clinton has not yet shown is that he is
prepared to make the tough choices. For the choices are, indeed, politically
difficult and the pay-off as long term as the problems are deep-seated.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
