<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Leading Article: Waging war
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH government's employment green paper, designed to curb the power
of an already enfeebled trade union movement, seemed a hangover from the
Thatcherite 1980s when it was first published last year. But now, after nine
quarters of recession and with the abolition of the wages councils tacked
on, the employment bill looks even more anachronistic.
The bill may still make good politics, providing Tory backbenchers with some
light relief from seeing the finances of trade unions put under pressure.
And there are elements of the bill which make good sense, in particular the
strengthening of the rights of individual trade union members. Yet in
deciding now to abolish the wages councils the government is taking a risk.
Attempting to reduce the wages of low-paid workers, at time of depressed
confidence, rising unemployment, and with the public sense of injustice
already aroused by the miners debacle, is not the most politic of actions.
In any case, the evidence does not suggest that the low levels set by the
wages councils have a significant negative employment effect, as the
government claims. By contrast, Labour's relatively high national minimum
wage would certainly have cost jobs. There is, in fact, a case for a system
of low but flexible wage floors as a way of preventing unscrupulous
employers from paying below market wages. The main weakness of the current
system is that, since 1986, the industry minima have been set nationally
rather than regionally.
Abolishing them now, in the current depressed economic climate, is likely to
do little more than reduce the wages of some low-paid workers, while
increasing the amount of family credit paid to those low-income households
that are adversely affected.
This government is showing again a rare taste for the wrong battles. Yes,
the UK faces great labour market challenges which require political
leadership. But trade union power and the wages of the low paid are low down
the list of problems. The government needs to devise strategies which can
reduce unemployment while keeping the real wage growth of above-average
earners under control when recovery comes. So far, on these issues the
government has had little to say and less to offer.
</TEXT>
