<DOCNO>FT924-9261</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8ADJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Arts: The Tender Husband
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ST GEORGE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Richard Steele, MP (1672-1729) was, according to Dr Johnson, 'the most
agreeable rake that ever trod the rounds of indulgence.' He co-founded the
original Spectator, Tatler and Guardian, invented the periodical essay, and
wrote a clutch of overlooked plays. The Magnificent Theatre Company has
revived The Tender Husband in a fine, fizzing production, now at the
Watermans Arts Centre.
The Tender Husband (1705) parodied middle class manners in an increasingly
bourgeois society; it looked back to Moliere, but introduced types later
used by Sheridan and Goldsmith.
Clerimont, the tender husband, has indulged his wife's capacious spending,
but now wants to shame her into frugality. His penurious younger brother,
condemned to an army career, settles on Biddy Tipkin, a rich, air-headed
romantic. But her ward, Hezekiah Tipkin, Lombard Street banker, wants her to
marry a wealthy West Country squire called Humphrey Gubbin, who in turn
loves Lucy Fainlove, the very woman whom Clerimont has disguised as a man
with hopes of compromising his wife. The tangle is cut by Samuel Pounce, an
obsequious lawyer: 'The Pounces will always have money, if there's any in
the world.'
The plot turns on love, money and opportunity. Nothing survives Steele's
Whiggish scrutiny: banking, country life, fashion, law, literature. The
play's principles remain simple: ''Tis by knowing what a man thinks of
himself, by giving him that, you may make him what you will.' Moral
questions never arise, for Steele speeds the action and forms his characters
by circumstance.
The directors, Lucie Fitchett and Ben Crocker respond to Steele's paciness.
The plain set and parody period costumes are a delight, with quilted cherubs
on Biddy's frock, and interlocking numbers on the banker's dress-coat. The
acting should deliver the satire with less fuss. But those who find the
right tone are Harriet Keevil as the sexy Lucy Fainlove, John Conroy as the
machinating Pounce and Simon Holmes as the bankrupted Clerimont shackled to
a connubial horror in organza.
Steele himself was a tender husband. He met his second wife at the funeral
of his first, and made sure he was always in touch. On February 16, 1716 he
wrote her this one-line gem: 'Dear Prue: Sober or not I am ever yours,
Richard Steele.'
Watermans Theatre, Brentford (081 568 1176) until November 14. Then on tour
to: Stamford, Berwick-upon-Tweed, Hexham, King's Lynn, Crewe, Blackpool,
Hemel Hempstead and Bury St Edmunds. Ends December 5
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9262</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8ADIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Arts: Sensuous sculpture - The sexuality of Victorian and
contemporary sculpture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SUSAN MOORE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pandora is the pivotal figure in two complementary sculpture shows in Stoke
on Trent. According to Hesiod, Zeus created Pandora, the first woman, as a
punishment for man's theft of fire. Hephaestus fashioned her out of clay,
Athena breathed life into her, and the other gods were invited to endow her
with every charm: hence Pandora or 'all-gifted'.
Hermes, however, gave her flattery and guile; and she was given a jar - not
a box - which she was forbidden to open. Curiosity apparently overcame her
and the vessel was opened, releasing all the evils and diseases of the world
from which man had hitherto been free. Only Hope was left crouching inside
the lid.
Harry Bates' marble Pandora represents the quintessence of late Victorian
art. The kneeling Pandora is indeed physical perfection, the gentle curves
of her bare flesh seem soft and yielding; her thigh voluptuously dimples
under the weight of the fateful casket. She is the paradox of the 'beautiful
evil' or 'deadly delight' of Greek myth and early Christian writing - and
here she is in like company.
The siren Circe and the temptress Eve also find a place in Reverie, Myth,
Sensuality: Sculpture in Britain 1880-1910, and with them the charge of
sexual frisson jumps up a volt. In Mackennal's bronze statuette Circe stands
erect, her arms and fingers outstretched, exercising her power to turn men
into swine, a metaphor for lust. So shocking were the cavortings of the
enslaved men depicted around the base that the sculpture was partially
swathed in red baize during its exhibition at the Royal Academy in 1894.
Sir Thomas Brock's monumental marble Eve is not the triumphant temptress,
but the sinner burdened with shame. Her head hangs low and she is too
wretched to even hide her nakedness. She stands exposed and vulnerable - and
every inch as invitingly tactile as Bates' Pandora. The other side of the
Victorian obsession with the virtuous and wicked woman emerges in
Reynolds-Stephens' Guinevere, showing the disgraced queen's redemption
through prayer and good works. The pervasive mood of these pieces is
contemplative, with the idealised human figure the most expressive metaphor
of mood and feeling.
This handsome survey reveals various aspects of the radical 'New Sculpture'
which emerged in Britain during the 1870s, a subject unjustly neglected
until a decade or so ago. These sculptures can be seen as three-dimensional
manifestations of the art of Rossetti, William Morris, Burne-Jones, Albert
Moore, Lord Leighton and GF Watts. Indeed Leighton and Watts were
painters-cum-sculptors, and Alfred Stevens was architect and designer too.
The movement's leading lights, Alfred Gilbert and George Frampton, pioneered
the use of polychromy in sculpture.
One of the primary aspirations of the New Sculptor was to expand the domain
of sculpture. Efforts were made to improve standards and to bring sculpture
back into the home. Gilbert produced numerous editions of bronzes in various
reduced sizes. Revealingly, the considerable succes d'estime enjoyed by the
New Sculptors did not guarantee financial security. Sir Alfred Gilbert was
bankrupted. The plaster model of Sir George Frampton's 'Mysteriarch' serves
as telling evidence of the difficulty sculptors faced in persuading a patron
to translate a model into expensive marble or bronze.
The Pandora myth provided the point of departure for a series of sculptures
and videos by the contemporary artist Rose Garrard which mark a neat
transition to the second show at Stoke, Traces of the Figure. All nine
contemporary artists make reference to the human body, albeit obliquely.
Subjectmatter is similarly ambiguous and unspecific, but the sexuality
implicit in the earlier work is now defiantly overt. This sexuality,
however, tends to be stripped of any eroticism. Deacon's 'The eye has it'
seems like a giant, trouser-tailed spermatozoa embarking on its journey;
Helen Chadwick similarly presents in triptych form a pair of fried eggs
flanked by barely visible organisms. Cathy de Monchaux both encases and
lines lead and steel tubes in lusciously soft red velvet.
More disturbingly, nature is relentlessly red in tooth and claw. Hermione
Wiltshire adds a cross-section to the hosier's dummy leg that shows the
blood, bone and muscles inside the real thing. Helen Chadwick's blown-up
images of the human scalp and a seething crown of worms that are horribly
suggestive of suppurating wounds, unsavoury bodily fluids and of mortality.
Of greatest presence is Alison Wilding's imperious construction draped with
black cloth. In this context, it stands like a funeral bier awaiting a body.
Stoke on Trent City Museum and Art Gallery until November 29; then to
Cartwright Hall, Bradford, from December 12-March 7, 1993.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9263</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8ADHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Arts: Forever Yours Marie Lou
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You recognise the scene at once, yes? All-too-closely-knit Welsh family,
locked into poverty. Papa Leopold fearsomely concerned with having the right
kind of peanut butter (smooth, not crunchy), and a selfish animal in bed;
weary mother Marie Louise - herself one of 14 siblings - pregnant with only
her fourth child; daughter Manon imitating her somnambulistic Roman Catholic
piety, sister Carmen finding a tacky kind of liberation as a
Country-and-Western chanteuse.
Not familiar? Well: the trouble is that this well-travelled 21-year-old play
is by Michel Tremblay, French Canada's leading playwright. Forever Yours
Marie Lou is one of his earliest plays, but like all of his work it is set
in a social and linguistic milieu which is as specific as could be. As
rendered in Welsh-English by the young Thin Language Theatre Company, it
becomes almost a surrealist exercise, unmoored to anything in real history
or life.
There are two reasons why Marie Lou struck a resonant chord which echoes
still for both French- and English-Canadian audiences. One is that it
captured the 1960s turning-point as it felt in Quebec, where within half a
generation that province stopped being a priest-ridden, wilfully 'backward'
community and joined the thrusting modern world. Almost overnight the Quebec
birthrate dropped from its traditional teeming high to Canada's lowest
(below replacement-level): and to get a book that was on the Index - Joyce,
Gide, Cocteau - from your local library you no longer had to ask for it in
English.
The other reason why the play has enjoyed so many productions is that its
poetic structure is fresh and sharply original. Though most of the action
takes place in the family kitchen/dining-room, it tacks continually between
a 'now' where the orphaned daughters argue over their family past, and an
earlier 'then' (at least ten years ago) when they were brutally subjected to
it. In that same room we witness the old parental rows and feel the
children's reactions and their older selves' bitter recall in ghostly
interpenetration. The grownup sisters' dialogues should alternate fluidly
with the horrid childhood scenes.
Sadly, the Thin Language product was far too clumsy with that
backward-and-forward switching to make it work. The script stammered
painfully - where a dialogue from one time should smoothly override one from
another, there were sudden, hiccoughing stage-waits. No dramatic rhythm or
pace; often, no clear indication of where or when these things were
happening. The stage-lighting might have helped but didn't, despite simple,
well-meant efforts by the technicians.
Though the storm-or-threatening forecasts prompted character-sketches along
the right lines, they registered here as shallow, unlocalised stereotypes,
never very funny or very moving. Native Forever Yours Mary Lou types might
relish the cynical tones of personal indictment, loud and unsparing, with
apologies only when caught out; but the Thin Language team recreates too
little sense of a real, stifling mini-world to trigger sympathetic responses
from the rest of us.
Battersea Arts Centre, Lavender Hill, SW11, until November 22
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9264</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8ADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Arts: Crime against Swan Lake - Ballet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Given publicity which reads: 'They tried to ban it, they alleged risque sex
scenes - next week you can see it', ballet audiences might suppose that they
were being lured to a cross between Vampire Lesbians of Sodom and the Kama
Sutra. But no] It is Northern Ballet Theatre's way of alerting us to the
charms of their Swan Lake. And, for once, I can agree with the publicity:
'they' should try to ban it. Not for any risque sex scenes - the production
has the erotic potential of a meringue - but for the sheer naughtiness of
asserting that this night out with the boys has anything much to do with
Swan Lake as a masterpiece of classical ballet.
Igor Stravinsky declared that a crime against a work of art started with a
crime against its text. NBT's staging, which I gather has wowed audiences in
the regions, recasts the traditional narrative so that it involves a
political coup, rejects all the accepted Ivanov/Petipa choreography, and
re-orders and (more excusably, given NBT's restricted means) re-orchestrates
Tchaikovsky's music. The resultant production - hectic in manner; desperate
in step - is entirely consonant with the policy of Christopher Gable, NBT's
director, to provide highly flavoured ballets for his largely regional
public.
My objections will be dismissed as those of a 'purist' - a term of
opprobrium in matters such as this, which I take as the highest of
compliments - who believes that Swan Lake, as shown by the Mariinsky or
Royal Ballets, has a noble identity owed to sublime lyric and bravura
choreography born of a superb dramatic score. But public appetite for
ballet's sacred titles, if not for a ballet's choreography, means that
managements know the truth of the dictum 'give them anything, but call it
Swan Lake'. Hence NBT's need for those two four-letter words, and the
necessity to turn the piece into the brawl that is on view at the Royalty
Theatre this week.
I sympathise with Gable's belief in dance drama, and in his wish to show
audiences that ballet can be directly and vividly communicative. He wins his
public with every staging. But I deplore the brutalisation of Swan Lake, its
miserable choreographic text by Dennis Wayne, its roller-skating bear, its
cohorts of swans who look like the deported drabs in Manon's third act, and
its meretricious dramatics. Above all, I despair at its absolute denial of
the power of classic academic dancing under the banner of one of classic
dancing's greatest achievements.
Northern Ballet Theatre is at the Royal Theatre this week with Swan Lake
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
