<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Costain expected to cut 300 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 300 jobs are expected to be lost at Costain as part of a campaign
to cut overheads by 30 per cent in the group's UK engineering and
construction division.
The move will swell the growing tide of redundancies in the recession-hit
construction industry - where more than 400,000 jobs have lost since summer
1989.
The construction and engineering division is to become Costain's largest on
the completion of the sale of its profitable Australian coal-mining business
for Pounds 123m to Peabody Coal, a subsidiary of Hanson, the Anglo-American
conglomerate.
As a first step Costain will close its engineering and construction division
headquarters in Woking, Surrey, and move staff to the group's headquarters
in south London. About 70 jobs are expected to go as a result.
The group also plans to rationalise its regional construction businesses
operating from a network of local offices. A further 250 jobs could go as a
result.
The redundancy package is expected to cost the group Pounds 800,000 for the
closure of the Woking office and about Pounds 3m for the rationalisation of
the division as a whole. Costain is expected to make savings of Pounds 8m a
year from the rationalisation.
The move is the latest in a series of actions by the group to generate cash
to reduce large borrowings. The number of UK-based employees, mostly in
engineering and construction, has fallen by 1,400 to 2,900 in the last 18
months.
Contractors have appealed to the government not to cut spending on large
infrastructure projects. They have warned that unemployment in the industry
will soar if projects like the Pounds 1.6bn extension to London
Underground's Jubilee Line are postponed.
</TEXT>
