<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Magistrate says move in public interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'THESE reports will be the guardian, rather than the foe, of justice and the
public interest,' said Mr Christopher Bourke, the magistrate in the case of
Mr Larry Trachtenberg, when he lifted reporting restrictions on the case,
John Mason writes.
His comment went to the core of the protracted legal argument over whether
the media should be able to fully report the court hearings.
Mr Trachtenberg, backed by the Serious Fraud Office, argued that the
hearings would attract widespread press coverage and that this might
prejudice his main trial, due to start in early 1994.
Mr Trachtenberg and the SFO pressed for restrictions to be imposed which
prevented the publication of any details which identified Mr Trachtenberg
personally or made any reference to the Maxwell affair.
They argued that public interest in the general question of defendants
refusing to answer section two questions after they had been charged could
still be served by anonymous reporting of the basic issues.
However, lawyers for newspapers argued that such limited reporting was
against the broad public interest and unworkable in practice. It could also
lead to rumour and confusion, since readers might think the trial concerned
the other defendants in the Maxwell case.
They also cited the decisions of the judges in the Guinness and Blue Arrow
fraud trials who had ruled that the public interest in the full reporting of
the first trials outweighed any possible prejudice to subsequent trials.
Mr Bourke initially applied the reporting restrictions, but lifted them two
weeks ago pending Mr Trachtenberg's appeal to the High Court for a judicial
review. Mr Trachtenberg's application was refused yesterday.
</TEXT>
