<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Management: From buckyballs to CNN - Christopher Lorenz
examines the latest thesis of guru Tom Peters, that all companies must
become as fast, flat and flexible as top service organisations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER LORENZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT MAY come as quite a surprise to the employees of several investment
banks, a telecommunications utility and an industrial hose maker to learn
that their organisations are seen as models which every company should
emulate in the future.
Television stations, advertising agencies, computer software houses, even
management consultancies - all have been lauded by various writers in recent
years as thriving on just the sort of informality, reduced hierarchy, rapid
responsiveness and project-based organisation which most people consider
necessary to competitive survival for almost every industry in the future.
But investment banks, telecoms carriers and hose makers? Not to speak of the
odd railway company, hand tool manufacturer, and giant engineering group?
Absolutely yes, according to Tom Peters, that tub-thumping American business
evangelist whose books, In Search of Excellence (1982) and Thriving on Chaos
(1987), sold millions and helped mould the attitudes and expectations of
untold numbers of managers and other employees in the US and Europe.
After an interval of five years, while he has stomped noisily around the
seminar and conference circuit in Billy Graham fashion, churning out
articles, newsletters, TV programmes and videos, Peters is back in hardcover
this month with a real vengeance. His new blockbuster, modestly titled
Liberation Management: Necessary Disorganisation For the Nanosecond
Nineties*, weighs in at an enormous 834 pages (22 of them merely displaying
its contents).
In spite of the time it takes to read (as I found to my cost this week), the
book could well become as influential in the next couple of years as
Excellence and Chaos.
As it makes clear via a flood of revealing case studies, Peters considers
that the sort of fast, flexible and flat - or flattish - organisation that
will prosper in the 1990s and beyond is epitomised to various degrees by
Goldman Sachs and other investment banks, by MCI, an ultra-lean
telecommunications carrier, and even by Titeflex, a humdrum hose offshoot in
Massachusetts of Britain's TI group. Peters also eulogises over revitalised
companies such as Union Pacific Railroad, the tools arm of Ingersoll Rand,
and ABB, Europe's most-admired engineering multinational.
Though several of these are manufacturers, Peters argues that they are just
as 'knowledge-based' as the sort of professional service organisations which
he posits as models.
The service organisations to which he gives particular praise include CNN,
Ted Turner's TV network, EDS, the systems integration group founded by Ross
Perot, and McKinsey, Peters's former management consultancy employer, as
well as a bevy of international advertising, design and 'event'
consultancies, notably Britain's Imagination group and part of the
Anglo-American IDEO design agency.
In one sense, Liberation Management is a comprehensively illustrated, racily
written compendium of almost every advanced management practice which has
begun to take root in recent years: not just 'delayering', high-involvement
and responsibility (or 'empowerment'), learning organisations, networks and
so on, but also vertical disintegration and 'outsourcing', total quality,
and fast development and production - which Peters says are part of the
'fashionisation' (ephemeral nature) of everything today.
The book also examines cross-functional teams, constantly shifting project
structures, and even the latest buzz phrase to grip industry, 'process
re-engineering'.
Underlying everything is Peters' advocacy of three basic principles:
breaking organisations into the smallest possible, 'independent' units;
giving every employee a businessperson's strong sense of revenue, cost and
profit; and getting far more involved than ever before with the customer.
But the compilation-like nature of the book does not mean that it lacks
originality. Peters not only relates the principles to each other more
effectively - and colourfully - than some of their original formulators, he
also provides plenty of insights of his own.
One is that the degree of control in flat, networked organisations often
outstrips that found in traditional bureaucracies. This is because of
several factors: project structures tend to focus members on tasks and keep
deadline pressure high; team members are motivated not to let down their
mates; customers are usually close at hand; and there is constant feedback.
Another insight is that the 'pecking order' found in project-based service
organisations such as McKinsey and EDS is very different from the
hierarchies or layers in a bureaucracy. Broadly speaking, anyone can talk to
anyone else and whom you 'report to' depends largely on the situation.
A third is that in these days of rampant subcontracting the construction and
maintenance of a company's 'core competences' does not necessarily mean
assembling a cast of thousands.
More controversial, though fundamental to his argument, is Peters'
insistence on the 'marketisation' of everything - including head office
staff roles. He urges adoption of a rule that every element of an
organisation, even staff and other support functions, demonstrates its
'fitness to compete' by selling a substantial share of its products or
services to the outside world. 'Allow market forces to blow a gale inside
the firm,' declares Peters. Though this may cut many a staff function down
to its appropriate size (often zero), it could also tempt a company to lose
control over core competences which need to remain proprietary.
Similarly, Peters does not come completely to grips with a question that
nags leading companies today: how to foster technical and other skills in a
'horizontal' organisation which has abandoned its previous 'functional'
specialists, and converted almost entirely to multi-disciplinary project
teams. Peters touches on solutions adopted by EDS and others, but does not
explore them fully.
Such cavils aside, Peters' rampaging new tome will delight more people than
it maddens, and instruct almost everyone. Where else, after all, could you
find between two covers a discussion of the organisational implications of
'buckyballs' - Buckminster fullerene carbon molecules, named after the
geodesic domes of American architect Buckminster Fuller, which are able 'to
have the bejesus beaten out of them and bounce back'? At the same time,
there is a case study from CNN's front line and a celebration of the work of
the market economist Friedrich Hayek. The only pity is that the covers of
the book are so damned far apart.
* Published Nov 12 in US by Knopf, Dollars 27.50, and on Nov 27 in UK by
Macmillan, Pounds 20.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9272</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8AC7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / The Property Market: Few come close to the ideal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The criteria used to judge property companies vying for Stoy Hayward's
annual award for financial reporting excellence highlight the need for
improvement in many areas of disclosure and treatment. Few property
companies come anywhere near scoring top marks in all areas.
The criteria have changed slightly over the three years of the award, but
the main categories have not. They include:
Introductory information. It should include a table of contents which is
comprehensive and detailed; financial highlights in summary at the front;
and a statement of company objectives including the types of business.
It should also include a record of performance over at least five years,
using indicators such as gross and rental income, value of total sales of
real property, value of all non-real property asset sales, total development
expenditure, pre-tax profits, dividends per share and net asset value.
Earnings per share should be shown in total and split between rental and
trading income.
Chairman's statement. There should be information on the economic and market
conditions over the past year and a forecast for the coming year; how the
company's results have been affected by market conditions; problems which
have materially affected the company's results; and significant investments
during the previous year.
There should be details of the strategy adopted by the management for the
coming year; a forecast of results in the next 12 months with an analysis of
the principal internal and external risks faced by the company; and a list
of the areas of business in which the company will be active in the future.
Accounting policies. The panel supports the capitalisation of interest - by
which interest payments are charged to the balance sheet and not taken as a
cost on the profit and loss account. It does not see it as an example of
'creative' accounting. However, there should be a clear statement of the
policy adopted and the amounts to be used. It believes companies should not
capitalise for more than one year after a building is finished, and that any
amounts capitalised should be net of tax relief.
Completed investment properties should be held in the accounts at their open
market value at the date of the balance sheet. Property investment companies
should have a full external valuation every year. The treatment of any
unrealised gain or deficit on revaluation should be shown.
There should be information on any property transfers between fixed and
current assets. The property should be transferred at book value. Investment
properties should be shown in a separate capital profit and loss account on
disposal, or shown as an extraordinary item.
How profits are taken on long-term projects prior to completion should be
disclosed. Profit should not be taken unless the outcome of the contract can
reasonably be foreseen - because the property has been pre-sold and
contracts exchanged.
Any goodwill - the difference between the price paid on an acquisition and
its net book value which is shown in the accounts - should be justified and
its accounting treatment explained.
Profit and loss account and notes. Income and expenditure related to
property investments, trading and other activities - including joint
ventures and listed and unlisted securities - should all be separately
identified. Trading income should be analysed by sector and location.
Balance sheet and notes. Property held for investments and property held for
dealing, and how much of each is under development, should be separately
itemised. There should be additional details by location, type, tenure, age
and rent review.
Borrowings - including the ability to alter the form of any loans and the
interest rate structure - should be shown, along with the timetable for
repayment, and the significance of those loans held in foreign currencies.
There should be details on deferred tax and potential capital gains payable.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
