<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Self-assessed tax plan is launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL INDIVIDUALS not taxed at source will be able to assess for themselves
the amount of tax they should pay under radical proposals launched yesterday
by the Inland Revenue.
The self-assessment system, described in a consultation document issued
yesterday, considerably broadens the scope of the system from proposals last
year which simply mooted the system for the self-employed.
Under the new version all other personal taxpayers receiving extra income -
such as freelance payments, interest on investments, casual work or rent on
a room - would be able to assess their own liability for tax. Income would
be taxed for the current year.
Those whose entire income is taxed at source through pay-as-you-earn schemes
would not be affected by the changes.
Taxpayers could still ask the Revenue to calculate their tax liability if
they wished.
For those using self-assessment, the Revenue would merely audit a small
number of tax submissions, while accepting payments on liabilities which
taxpayers had calculated themselves.
The current tax system requires taxpayers to submit details of their income
and assets, which is then assessed by the Revenue which calculates the tax
to be paid.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said in a foreword to the document: 'The
proposals would make the personal tax system simpler and fairer. But they
would involve considerable changes for taxpayers, tax advisers and the
Inland Revenue.'
The proposals would not be introduced until the 1995-96 tax year at the
earliest, and then in a transitional form - with full introduction planned
for 1996-97.
The Revenue said the consultative document issued last year on
self-assessment for the self-employed - those with schedule D tax returns -
had been widely welcomed and there had been strong support to extend the
system to other taxpayers.
It has asked for submissions in response to the proposals by January 31.
A Simpler System for Assessing Personal Tax. Inland Revenue, Inland Revenue
Reference Room, Room 8, New Wing, Somerset House, London WC2R 1LB. Pounds 2.
</TEXT>
