<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Councils warn of rise in tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authorities claim government plans to tighten the collection of
business rates could lead to unexpected increases in next year's council tax
bills.
The Local Government Chronicle says today that the plans have 'angered
council treasurers', who fear that council tax bills will be significantly
higher than original government estimates of between Pounds 267 and Pounds
800.
The business rate is set by the government, but councils collect it.
Under proposals set out in a consultation document, councils deemed by the
Department of the Environment and the district auditor not to be diligent in
collecting rates will be liable to make good the shortfall.
Councils pay their business rate revenue into the national non-domestic
rates pool, which bears all the costs of non-collection.
The consultation document proposes that councils should no longer be able to
adjust their payments to the fund for non-collection 'where collection of
debts has been jeopardised by poor collection and enforcement performance'.
The Department of the Environment said the change was necessary because
claims by councils for non-collection would no longer be audited before
being submitted.
'We have no evidence that local authorities are making unduly high provision
for bad debts,' it added.
Last year 95 per cent of the assessed business rate was collected
nationwide.
Mr Ewan Rayner, president of the Association of District Council Treasurers,
said the proposed rule was 'extremely unfair' because it could place
additional burdens on council tax payers 'who can have no responsibility
whatsoever for business rates non-payment'.
The head of Britain's leading association for local tax experts yesterday
warned that many people in local government had a 'death wish' over the
introduction of the council tax.
Mr Colin Farrington, director of the Institute of Revenues, Rating and
Valuation said: 'Whatever short-term difficulties there may be, it is time
for us to reiterate that the new property tax for local government is
basically sound.'
</TEXT>
