<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Thatcher's union regime lives on
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MAKERS OF artificial flowers will soon find, after more than 80 years of
statutory wage protection, that their wages are set according to the harsh
dictates of the international market place.
The government's decision to abolish the 26 remaining wages councils,
announced yesterday, in effect ends Britain's system of statutory industry
minimum wages.
The councils set wages floors for 2.5m low-paid private-sector workers,
about 10 per cent of the workforce, and covered industries as diverse as
catering, hairdressing, laundries, and ostrich-feather workers.
The decision is intended to be a significant political signal from the
government that it is continuing the deregulatory agenda of the then Mrs
Margaret Thatcher when she was prime minister. Yet whether abolition will
increase efficiency and employment in the labour market is highly
contentious. A number of recent studies have suggested that these minimum
wages may even increase employment.
The government has consistently argued that wages councils, by distorting
the labour market, have reduced industrial efficiency and cut jobs. It
repeatedly made clear that it saw no medium term role for the councils and
their influence has declined significantly in recent decades.
The average hourly minimum set by the councils has declined steadily since
1979 as a percentage of the economy-wide average wage. More importantly, the
degree of wage variation within industries covered by councils has also
risen, suggesting that an increasing number of companies are paying wages
above the minimum.
British business has, not surprisingly, been calling for the councils to be
abolished for years in the face of union opposition. The Institute of
Directors argues that the councils constitute a bureaucratic and arbitrary
intervention in the labour market, which is especially onerous on businesses
employing less than 50 people.
A recent report from Income Data Services, the employment research body,
lists complaints from catering and retail companies such as Grand
Metropolitan and from the National Federation of Meat Traders.
The system, they say, is inflexible and arbitrary. The fixed national
minimums make it difficult to introduce pay structures which regard
performance or reflect regional variations in living costs or labour supply.
However, many smaller companies support the retention of wages councils,
according to the IDS survey, because they provide an uncomplicated guide for
wage-setting while preventing larger companies from competing by wage
cutting.
The government acknowledges businesses' complaints, but stresses two other
reasons for abolition: that they reduce employment by keeping wages
artificially high, and that they do so while playing a neg-ligible role in
preventing poverty.
The government claims that 80 per cent of those affected, primarily
part-time women workers, live in households with at least one other income.
So a fall in low wages would not increase poverty significantly.
Although no detailed study exists on the income characteristics of workers
in wage council industries, a study by the Institute for Fiscal Studies on
the income effects of the Labour party's plan to introduce a statutory
minimum wage appears to support the government's conclusions.
The IFS report found that wage floors were a surprisingly blunt way to
attack poverty because most low-wage workers come from high-income
households. The gains from Labour's minimum wage would be concentrated among
middle-income households with the richest 30 per cent having a larger net
gain than the poorest 30 per cent.
Yet minimum wages may still be well targeted on low-income working families,
according to Mr Paul Gregg of the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research.
He finds that a national minimum wage would raise the incomes of more than
half of the poorest 10 per cent of families in which one person works. Most
poor people do not work. But abolishing existing minimum wages may well
increase poverty among the working poor.
Nor is the government's case on the employment effects of abolishing wage
councils very sound. In some highly competitive manufacturing sectors the
evidence suggests that raising wages reduces employment. That was a
conclusion of a Department of Employment study of the UK textile industry in
1985.
In the service sector the evidence - both in the US and the UK - is less
clear cut. A recent study of the employment effects of UK wages councils,
conducted by Mr Stephen Machin and Mr Alan Manning at the London School of
Economics, finds no evidence that the decline in the effectiveness of wages
councils in the 1980s has increased employment.
In the catering industry the results seem to suggest the opposite.
Employers, they argue, have found it profitable to reduce the wages they
pay. But this makes it harder to recruit people and thus reduces employment,
a pattern that can also be seen in the US hamburger industry - not at all
the effect that the government intends.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
