<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Basic pay set for 10 per cent of workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN wages councils were set up in 1909 their brief was to encourage the
development of voluntary collective bargaining in industries where unions
had been weak, Catherine Milton writes.
In the industries covered by today's wages councils four fifths of employees
are women working part-time.
The Department of Employment has recently indicated that two thirds of the
workers whose wages are set by the councils are above the minimum rates
which vary between Pounds 2.60 and Pounds 3 an hour.
The councils were set up by the Trade Boards Act which established minimum
pay rates for workers in the 'sweated trades'.
Winston Churchill, then president of the Board of Trade, told the Commons:
'It is a serious national evil that any class of His Majesty's subjects
should receive less than a living wage in return for their utmost
exertions.'
By 1953 there were 66 councils covering 3.5m workers. Since then some
councils have become redundant, others abolished or amalgamated.
The 1986 Wages Act reduced the scope of the councils' influence, removing
workers aged under 21 and requiring councils only to set a single adult
hourly rate and overtime rate.
The councils are made up of workers' and employers' representatives, chaired
by one of three independent conciliators who cast their votes if the two
sides cannot agree.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
