FT  06 NOV 92 / Ex-minister questions DTI licence descriptions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DESCRIPTIONS by manuf-acturers of the final use of their products are
'hardly relevant' when they apply to the Department of Trade and Industry
for export licences, Mr Alan Clark, a former trade minister, told an Old
Bailey court yesterday, John Mason writes.
He was giving evidence in the trial of three former directors of Matrix
Churchill, the Coventry machine tool maker, who deny breaching export
regulations by telling the DTI that equipment to be exported to Iraq was for
civilian not military use.
'Saying what it is for is hardly relevant,' Mr Clark said. 'The point is
what can it do.'
The trial continues today.
