<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: MPs hold Major's post-dated cheque
 -Ivo Dawnay counts the cost of the prime minister's narrow victory against
the Maastricht renegades in the Commons
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER the party, the bill. Mr John Major's revelation that the Commons will
not complete ratification of the Maastricht treaty until after the Danes
hold a second referendum, roughly pencilled in for May, looks set to provoke
groans on the Continent.
There is every possibility that this was the post-dated cheque that bought
the three crucial votes which won the embattled prime minister the day.
Yesterday, as the Tory Euro-sceptics regrouped, their defectors defended
their wounded pride by blaming the brutal tactics of the whips.
If a lengthy ratification process was the price Mr Major paid, the quality
of his victory is seriously impaired and his ego is not left unbruised.
Arguably well short of a U-turn, the concession still bears all the signs of
an 11th-hour deal offered even after he had made his speech and found that
the voting figures still failed to add up. If that is the case, Mr Major's
authority cannot be assumed to be fully rehabilitated.
How did the prime minister manage to get himself into such a damaging
confrontation - a struggle that at one point left both his own future and
that of the treaty itself seriously under threat?
With hindsight, the showdown became inevitable when, last June, Mr Major
promised Mr Neil Kinnock, then the Labour leader, a routine debate on the
bill before it went to committee stage.
That was before the Danish referendum and Britain's humiliating ejection
from the exchange rate mechanism. After Black Wednesday, Mr Major appeared
to have opted for the safer path of holding the debate but putting intensive
Commons discussion of the treaty text on the back-burner until after next
month's Edinburgh summit.
His statement on September 24 that the committee stage of the bill would be
postponed to await Danish developments and new language on subsidiarity
appeared to satisfy the doubters.
However, the warm reception for the prime minister's speech at the annual
party conference in Brighton early last month has boosted efforts by the
cabinet's pro-European wing to capitalise on the goodwill and take on his
enemies within.
The still unexplained about-turn that led to this week's debate was provoked
at least in part by the attacks on Mr Major's leadership qualities after the
row and consequent U-turn over the coal-mine closures.
It was further hardened when the Euro-sceptic right objected strenuously to
the announcement by Mr Tony Newton, leader of the House, that the government
would table a substantive - as opposed to purely technical motion - for
debate.
That move provoked Lord Tebbit, the fiercely anti-Maastricht former party
chairman, to launch a direct and undisguised dismissal of the prime
minister's personal commitment to ratification. He suggested, woundingly:
'Maastricht is more important that any individual and therefore whether the
prime minister would resign or not is not material in the terms of the
debate.'
Journalists travelling with Mr Major to El Alamein the following weekend
were convinced that it was this remark which provoked the undenied reports
that the PM would call an election if his will was thwarted.
In the next 10 days, the run-up to the debate became a head-on battle of
wills between the two sides. At first the Euro-sceptics appeared to make the
running. A meeting of the rightwing 92 Group showed speakers lined up 21 to
nine against Mr Major's approach. His apparent election threat was dismissed
as 'silly and petulant' by one MP.
The following day, Downing Street gave ground, conceding that the prospect
of an election was 'not relevant'. But there was no quarter given on the
government's determination to table a substantive motion as Mr Major
launched a charm offensive from his Commons office.
Within a day, Labour's shadow cabinet set the scene for a showdown by
committing the party to outright opposition on the grounds that any debate
would, in effect, be a vote of confidence in the government and Mr Major.
That stance appeared, at least in part, to be vindicated by an ambiguous
reply from Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary. At Foreign Office
questions, he said the Commons would have to decide whether it wanted the
prime minister to preside over the Edinburgh summit - preserving and
extending the influence of Britain in Europe - or whether it did not.
Deftly Mr Jack Cunningham, his shadow, ignored the sub-clause and asked:
'How do you expect us to support that?'
As tension mounted, Mr Major launched an impassioned and well-received
appeal to the backbench 1922 Committee before a weekend of frantic telephone
lobbying by the whips.
Still the discipline and determination of the anti-treaty lobby remained
intact, provoking ever more dire warnings from the cabinet.
Raising the stakes, Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
warned that a defeat for the government would leave a 'policy vacuum of
incalculable destructiveness'.
Mr David Hunt, the Welsh secretary, appeared to vindicate Labour's claims
further by arguing in a BBC interview on Sunday: 'We have to show confidence
not only in the government but in the prime minister.'
As the numbers still failed to add up, speculation mounted at Westminster of
a behind-the-scenes deal - most probably with the Ulster unionists. Even Mr
Major's apparently desperate claim to those trooping into his Commons office
that he was 'the biggest Euro-sceptic in the cabinet' failed to deliver the
breakthrough.
By the day of the debate, the members' lobby resembled a goldfish bowl
invaded by sharks as the circling whips pressed their case. Allegations of
calls to tearful wives, missions to constituency chairmen and all the other
ungentlemanly conduct with which the whips are sometimes associated have all
been made.
The bottom line was the three votes that won the day - three votes that may
prove the most important in Mr Major's career.
By the time it comes to a final decision - possibly as late as October next
year - the government hopes that an official Labour abstention on the third
reading will ensure they are never as vulnerable again.
Nonetheless, one tranche of Danegeld has already been paid.
</TEXT>
