FT  06 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Visa clampdown for Yugoslavs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST nationals of the former Yugoslavia will need to get a visa before
travelling to the UK from midnight tomorrow, Mr Kenneth Clarke, home
secretary, announced yesterday.
The requirement will be imposed on all former Yugoslavs except those holding
passports issued by the governments of Croatia and Slovenia.
The UK has already admitted about 40,000 Yugoslavs, with 4,424 applying for
asylum. Mr Clarke said he would tell the United Nations and the Red Cross
that Britain could take 150 former detainees from this weekend. It would
also accept their dependants, making about 600 people in all.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said: 'You may have given hope to that
small group of people with one hand, but by your announcement on visa
requirements today you are taking hope away from many more with the other
hand.'
