<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tory rebels vow to carry on
campaign
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY'S defeat was a bitter pill for the Tory rebels to swallow. But
there is plenty of fight left in their camp.
Their intention is clearly to battle through the remaining stages of the
Maastricht Bill with all the strength and guile they can muster. 'There
certainly will be the use of every tactic that is appropriate,' one of the
rebel leaders said yesterday.
The rebels will find it difficult to derail the treaty's progress towards
ratification - their ideal objective. But they may well delay it
significantly, which for them is the next best thing.
To force the one change in the treaty's text that could prove fatal,
arithmetic suggests they would need to find common ground with Labour in
voting for an amendment to the implementing bill.
This will not be easy. Mr Michael Spicer, one of the rebel leaders, said
yesterday: 'We have got nothing in common with Labour generally. There is no
way we would co-operate on the sorts of things they want.'
To delay the bill's passage, however, they would merely have to help ensure
that the government did not obtain a guillotine or a series of closure
motions restricting the time for debate.
Although the bill itself stretches to just three clauses and less than one
side of an A4 sheet of paper, Tory rebels and other MPs have already tabled
sufficient amendments and suggested new clauses to fill a densely packed
65-page document. To debate all these proposals in full could take years.
The indication yesterday that the government was prepared to delay the
bill's third reading until after a second Danish referendum suggests,
however, that the government would like to see the committee stage finished
by May.
Such a deadline might trigger an old-fashioned war of attrition, involving a
long sequence of late-night sittings with MPs on call at virtually any hour
in case a division was called.
In this situation, the rebels would probably dig in their heels and seek to
delay the government for as long as possible.
As they did so, they would be encouraged by the hope that the Danes might
achieve their most cherished objective for them by rejecting the treaty for
a second time.
This would, of course, enable them to claim victory and to argue that the
government was wrong to waste valuable Commons time debating a document that
was destined not to be ratified.
In terms of finding common ground with Labour in a bid to force changes to
the bill at the committee stage, rebels suggest that the best bet could be
an amendment urging the government to hold a British referendum.
This could attract support from a significantly larger number of Tories than
those who opposed the government on Wednesday night. It would also be backed
by a sizeable contingent of Labour anti-Maastrichteers. However, it is
unlikely to be backed by the Labour leadership.
Even winning the battle to have an amendment carried would not amount to a
decisive victory in the campaign. The government could succeed in reversing
the change at the bill's report stage.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
