<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Clinton team gets to grips with tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONGRESSIONAL staff are already getting down to work on new tax measures to
head the agenda facing the new Congress, which will convene next year.
Economic advisers to Governor Bill Clinton, the Democratic president-elect,
have indicated they hope to have a job creation package ready to present to
Congress soon after his inauguration on January 20.
But on Wednesday President George Bush, in his final tussle with the
outgoing Congress, vetoed a Dollars 27bn (Pounds 17.4bn) tax bill passed in
October. Aides said yesterday the veto would probably speed the process of
introducing tax legislation in the new Congress.
The vetoed tax bill grew out of an urban aid package proposed in the wake of
riots that broke out in Los Angeles at the end of April and included many
measures sought by Mr Bush - among them the creation of a number of
enterprise zones and the repeal of a controversial luxury tax on boats.
But the Democratic majority in Congress added other measures that the
president disagreed with, and which would have broken his renewed pledge not
to raise taxes. They delayed sending the bill to the president to give him
the opportunity to sign it after the pressure of the election was over. He
passed up this opportunity, signing a veto message on the flight back to
Washington the day after the election.
Congressman Dan Rostenkowski, who as chairman of the House ways and means
committee holds the keys to all US tax legislation, says the initiative now
lies with Mr Clinton. 'He's going to have to call the tune. I'll tell him to
be bold,' the veteran Illinois congressman said.
High on Mr Clinton's list of priorities is a targeted investment tax credit.
Influential members of Congress are likely to want to revive several of the
measures
included in the vetoed tax bill. The repeal of the luxury boat tax, for
example, is close to the heart of Senate majority leader George Mitchell,
whose home state of Maine harbours a significant boat-building industry.
Another measure, to expand the tax-sheltered Individual Retirement Accounts,
has been championed by Senator Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, who chairs the Senate
finance committee.
Once a tax bill is on the road, congressional tax experts say, members will
use it as a vehicle to which they can attach any number of additional
measures, including legislation targeting taxes paid by foreign companies in
the US.
The issue is a contentious one, and the Internal Revenue Service is still
waiting to see what the yield will be of new legislation passed in 1989 and
1990, which imposed stiffer record-keeping and reporting requirements on
foreign companies.
Multinational groups can shift the balance of their profits between
countries by charging higher or lower transfer prices for goods and services
exchanged within the group. International rules dictate that transfer prices
should be established on the 'arm's length' principle, as if the goods or
services were sold to an unrelated company. For intangibles, however, an
arm's length price can be difficult to establish.
A number of congressmen, led by Democrat Jake Pickle of Texas and Republican
Duncan Hunter of California, claim widespread abuse of transfer pricing
rules has allowed foreign companies to shift billions of dollars of profits
abroad, so escaping US taxation.
Much of the criticism is based on 1986, when foreign companies in aggregate
reported a net loss of Dollars 1.5bn, although those companies that did
report profits paid aggregate taxes of Dollars 3bn.
In 1988, the latest year for which full statistics are available, foreign
company profits amounted to only 1.4 per cent of sales, compared with an
average 3.7 per cent of sales for US companies. But the General Accounting
Office, an investigative arm of Congress, concluded this discrepancy 'did
not prove the existence of a widespread problem'.
Already, the US's efforts to squeeze more taxes out of for-
eign companies have run into international criticism. Earlier this year the
Treasury had to withdraw a set of proposed regulations relating to Section
482 of the Internal Revenue Code, which governs transfer pricing.
The fiscal affairs committee of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation
and Development (OECD), the Paris-based grouping of 24 industrial nations,
said in a letter to Mr Nicholas Brady, Treasury secretary, that the proposed
regulations 'would seriously disrupt existing international taxation
arrangements, with adverse effects on the economic relations between member
countries'.
However, Mr Clinton's economic programme assumes that it will be possible,
just from tougher enforcement of existing rules, to raise an additional
Dollars 9bn from foreign corporations in 1993, rising to Dollars 13.5bn in
1996 - a total of Dollars 45bn over four years.
Realistic estimates of the available extra revenue range from Dollars 166m
to Dollars 1bn a year. The more extreme estimates are, for the most part,
more illustrative calculations based on the arbitrary assumption that
foreign corporations' profits ought to match the return on Treasury bonds.
A rigorous clampdown on transfer pricing is likely to raise more money from
US-based multinationals' arrangements with their overseas subsidiaries than
from foreign companies operating in the US. Only about 13 per cent of the
money involved in pending Section 482 cases involves foreign companies.
Political realities suggest some foreign taxation measure will be added to
any new tax bill.
Tax lawyers working with foreign companies in Washington appear confident
that the more extreme proposals will not come to pass. These include an idea
floated in a discussion bill issued by Mr Rostenkowski this summer, which
would tax foreign companies on the assumption that their earnings equalled
at least three quarters of the average profitability of US businesses in the
same sector.
'I do believe in the end the ways and means committee will recognise that
there is simply not Dollars 45bn out there,' one Washington lawyer
concluded.
 -------------------------------------------------------
     AGGREGATE FEDERAL TAX LIABILITY AND INCOME OF
                 FOREIGN-OWNED COMPANIES
 -------------------------------------------------------
Year            Tax         Income         Profit
             liability    (Dollars bn)    margin on
            (Dollars bn)                  sales (%)
 -------------------------------------------------------
1983            1.8          1.8            0.5
1984            4.5          4.5            1.0
1985            3.6          3.0            0.6
1986            3.0         -1.5           -0.3
1987            4.6          5.6            0.8
1988            5.8         11.2            1.4
