<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Top Treasury official quits for First Boston
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR David Mulford, US Treasury under-secretary for international affairs, is
to join the CS First Boston group next week, the US Treasury announced
yesterday.
Mr Mulford, the longest-serving senior US Treasury official responsible for
international economic policy since the second world war, is one of the
first members of the Republican administration to announce his departure
following Democratic Governor Bill Clinton's victory in the presidential
election.
His move, to become vice-chairman of First Boston in New York and deputy
chairman of Credit Suisse First Boston in London, represents a return to the
world of investment banking for Mr Mulford, 55, after 8 1/2 years at the US
Treasury.
He will be a member of First Boston's operating committee in New York with
special responsibility for Latin America. Mr Mulford was closely involved
with the region during his time at the US Treasury, helping to develop and
implement the Baker and Brady plans for easing the Latin American debt
crisis and playing a large role in producing President George Bush's
Enterprise for the Americas initiative.
He served at the Treasury first as assistant secretary for international
affairs and from May 1989 as under-secretary. His departure comes as no
surprise - he is known to have been considering various job offers for
several months.
Since entering the Treasury in March 1984 he has been the Group of Seven
deputy responsible for co-ordinating economic policies with other members of
the bloc of leading industrial nations. He helped develop the 1985 Plaza
Accord to curb the dollar's strength and since 1986 has been the one of the
US team preparing the annual world economic summit as 'financial sherpa'.
He chaired negotiations with Japan to open and liberalise Japanese capital
markets and has played a prominent role for the US in international
discussions on assistance for Russia.
As a tough and sometimes brutal negotiator, Mr Mulford has earned respect
rather than affection in his dealings with officials from other countries.
The policies he has espoused have sometimes been controversial. Some
economists criticised the Brady initiative for having deterred banks from
lending new money to the debtor nations. Mr Mulford believes the Brady
initiative was one of the great successes of US economic diplomacy in the
late 1980s and played an essential part in bringing Latin American nations
back into the mainstream of the world economy.
Mr Mulford and Mr Nicholas Brady, the US Treasury secretary after whom the
plan was named, were quicker than European policy makers to warn that the
world economy was slowing down at the end of the 1980s.
Mr Mulford has always pursued an international career. He spent 20 years in
international investment banking before moving to the Treasury.
After leaving the Treasury he will keep in touch with public affairs through
the Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington, where he
will be a special adviser.
