<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / New US tax legislation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Attempts by the US to introduce new tax legislation affecting foreign
corporations could lead to tit-for-tat retaliation from other countries.
An obvious candidate in the UK would be for the Inland Revenue to withhold
the refund to US-owned companies on advance corporation tax (ACT) levied on
the dividends paid to shareholders.
A precedent for retaliation does exist. Legislation was introduced in 1985
in the UK in response to unitary tax laws in California and can be triggered
at any time if a current appeal on its applicability to UK companies is
lost.
However, the Revenue sees no way that this could be used in response to Mr
Clinton's proposals.
