<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Foreigners keep their cool on US tax threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US President-elect Bill Clinton's promise to crack down on the tax practices
of foreign companies has so far failed to cause much consternation in
corporate boardrooms overseas.
Most are waiting to see how far campaign threats will translate into
realities once the new president settles into negotiations and sees the
difficulties of implementation.
Mr Michael Garner, finance director of TI, the UK-headquartered engineering
group, said: 'Without sounding too cavalier, we have seen these things come
and go before. If the proposals get too Draconian, sanity usually prevails.'
The threat to TI from new transfer-pricing rules would not be significant,
because the company manufactured in the US rather than importing goods for
the US market.
However, Mr Nick Cunningham, an analyst with Societe Generale Strauss
Turnbull, the securities house, said: 'At the very best, the US Internal
Revenue Service is going to get tougher.
At worst, they will introduce arbitary unitary taxation under which foreign
companies would be hammered.'
Mr Cunningham has made tentative calculations for seven UK companies with
substantial US operations which show that all but one are paying below full
US corporate tax, and would have reported earnings per share more than 20
per cent lower if they were subject to unitary tax.
One of the principal mechanisms companies were likely to lose was the
ability to use 'debt arbitrage,' he said. This involves taking out
borrowings in the US which are deductible against US tax, and investing them
at higher interest rates in the UK, where the taxable interest can be offset
against advance corporation tax payable on dividends.
Tax experts yesterday were busy providing advice on strategies which
companies should adopt in response to the election of Mr Clinton.
Mr Bruce Lassman, head of the US tax desk at Ernst &amp; Young, the accountancy
firm, stressed a number of actions which would save tax.
Transfer pricing: Companies should examine transfer pricing methods and
gather documentary support to help justify the system in future negotiations
with the IRS.
Foreign investors' capital gains tax: sales of US subsidiaries now would
protect them from possible future capital gains taxes.
'Earnings strippings': pre-paying rents, royalties, management charges and
other payments should protect companies from future legislation which limits
'excessive' tax relief on payments paid to foreign companies.
Lobbying expenses: lobbying may be disallowed for tax deductions, so
companies should lobby against the legislation and enter binding lobbying
contracts before any change.
Worker training: pre-paying salaries and bonuses before any changes, such as
Mr Clinton's proposal requiring all employers to contribute 1.5 per cent of
payroll to worker retraining, is recommended.
Investment tax credit: delaying capital expenditure to take advantage of a
Clinton-proposed 10 per cent credit on new capital investment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
