FT  06 NOV 92 / BA-USAir decision by Christmas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US aviation authorities will make a decision before Christmas on whether to
let British Airways acquire a large minority stake in USAir, the
sixth-largest US carrier.
Mr Andrew Card, US transportation secretary, said yesterday the
decision-making process would be an open one. He has instigated a formal
'comment' period, which allows interested parties to submit their views by
November 27. Comments in response would then be due by December 11 and Mr
Card's ruling would be made by December 24.
The department has already received considerable correspondence on the issue
 -not least from the 'Big Three' US airlines, which oppose the deal. The
correspondence will be placed on public file, and the department has ordered
both British Airways and USAir to do the same with information they have
already provided to it.
The department said the deal 'would result in changes in USAir's operations,
financial structure and management', and raised the question of whether the
airline would 'continue to operate under the control of US citizens'.
The final decision will be made by Mr Card, despite the impending change in
presidential administrations. During the election campaign President George
Bush and Governor Bill Clinton voiced differing views on the deal, which
involves a Dollars 750m (Pounds 483.8m) British Airways investment in USAir.
The president was carefully non-committal about the transaction's overall
merits, although he had previously favoured more foreign investment in US
airlines. But Mr Clinton said during a TV chat show that he had 'real
problems with it'.
'We get no access to the British market if we do it,' he said but, in
response to a further question, replied that he would not 'sign off' on the
deal.
