<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Rawlings heads for surprise poll victory
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE, Africa Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FLIGHT Lieutenant Jerry John Rawlings, Ghana's military leader, was last
night headed for a surprise victory in the country's first democratic
presidential elections in 13 years.
The outcome was challenged by opposition leaders, but government supporters
hailed it as a triumph for the 45-year-old former air force pilot over four
other candidates.
Semi-official figures announced on state-run radio from 198 of the 200
constituencies gave Flt Lt Rawlings 58.6 per cent of the vote.
If his lead is maintained in the last remaining constituencies, the
charismatic Flt Lt Rawlings will be elected president in a single round of
polling.
Opposition candidates said the voting should be annulled because of
widespread vote rigging. In the central Ghanaian city of Kumasi, an
opposition stronghold, a dusk-to-dawn curfew was imposed after riots broke
out when results were released showing Flt Lt Rawlings in the lead.
An interim report by a 15-member Commonwealth observer group said the
elections were free and fair. But the process had 'not been without
incident', the report continued, citing 'admitted imperfections in the
voters' roll and the organisation and conduct of some polling stations'.
'Most of what we are hearing so far are problems of organisation and
training rather than deliberate mischief,' said Mr Richard Joseph, head of
an observer team sent by the Carter Centre of former US President Jimmy
Carter. 'The real instances of malfeasance are really just a handful.'
Flt Lt Rawlings' closest rival, Prof Albert Adu Boahen, had 30.2 per cent of
the poll and the three other candidates were trailing further behind.
Flt Lt Rawlings will have achieved a remarkable victory if he has succeeded
in converting an unpopular austerity reform programme, implemented under his
heavy- handed 11-year rule, into a winning electoral programme.
His supporters said that he had received widespread support from rural
peasants, who make up more than 75 per cent of the population and who have
benefited from the reforms through much increased producer prices for
agriculture and cocoa and mass programmes of rural electrification.
Parliamentary elections are due to take place on December 8.
</TEXT>
