<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Japan's LDP 'tried to pay off extremists'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE REPUTATION of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic party (LDP) was further
tarnished yesterday when Tokyo prosecutors alleged that senior party
officials offered a total of Y5bn (Pounds 25.3m) to an extreme right-wing
group to stop a public campaign against the party.
Prosecutors were presenting evidence to a Tokyo District Court trial of
executives at Tokyo Sagawa Kyubin, the trucking company at the centre of an
illegal donation scandal, when they yesterday outlined alleged dealings
between seven LDP leaders and the far right group, Kominto.
Mr Shin Kanemaru, the godfather of Japanese politics, resigned last month
after admitting that he accepted a Y500m donation from Tokyo Sagawa. He was
also under suspicion, as are several other LDP politicians, of having
regular contact with a prominent gangster organisation.
However, the ruling party was shaken by the unexpected prosecutors'
statements yesterday, as they lengthened the list of senior officials who
attempted use gang links, money or personal contacts to silence Kominto,
which launched a noisy campaign against a former prime minister, Mr Noboru
Takeshita, in 1987.
There was further embarrassment when the prosecutors said Mr Kanemaru had
contacted executives at a leading Japanese commercial bank last year to ask
that it provide assistance to the financially troubled Tokyo Sagawa.
The prosecutors ensured that the LDP's largest faction, formerly run by Mr
Kanemaru, would remain in turmoil, as they alleged that Mr Keizo Obuchi, the
new faction head, had used 'agents' to persuade Kominto to end its campaign
against Mr Takeshita.
Mr Obuchi said he had no direct contact with Kominto, but four of the six
other politicians mentioned by the prosecutors conceded that they or their
representatives had arranged meetings with the group, well known for both
its use of violence and its underworld links.
The new allegations threaten to dominate the present sitting of the Japanese
parliament, which is supposed to give its approval to an emergency economic
package announced by the government in August.
Opposition parties have wanted Mr Takeshita to testify under oath about his
links to Tokyo Sagawa, but there may now be a move to force all seven
politicians listed yesterday to answer questions in parliament.
Naming the politicians was an apparent reaction by the prosecutors to strong
public criticism of their handling of the illegal donation case against Mr
Kanemaru, who was not questioned directly and did not face a court action,
in spite of admitting that he broke the Political Funds Control Law.
</TEXT>
