FT  06 NOV 92 / Savimbi willing to seek peace, says Botha
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRETORIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR PIK BOTHA, South African foreign minister, said yesterday Mr Jonas
Savimbi, Angola's rebel Unita leader, was willing to seek peace in the
country, Reuter reports from Pretoria.
He told a news conference he had spoken to Mr Savimbi on Wednesday following
fighting between Unita forces and Angolan government troops that killed some
1,200. 'He indicated firmly and clearly his willingness, despite tremendous
emotional stress, to continue with the democratic process. . .and play a
constructive role,' Mr Botha said.
There was no immediate response from the government in Luanda, which South
Africa informed about the conversation. But Angolan diplomats in Lisbon said
government and Unita officials had held talks to end fighting in the towns
of Lobito and Benguela. The last pockets of fighting in the capital Luanda
appeared to have died down.
The European Community, meanwhile, said it would hold any party that blocked
the peace process responsible for its actions. A statement issued in London
called on all parties to abide by a ceasefire negotiated by the United
Nations on Monday.
The ex-Marxist MPLA won United Nations-supervised elections which Mr Savimbi
later denounced as a fraud.
