<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / India's economic reforms defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR Indian policy-maker said yesterday that economic reform was going
ahead 'at a gradual pace', rejecting any suggestion that the government's
programme was running out of steam.
Mr Montek Singh Ahluwalia, the economic affairs secretary and top economic
adviser to Mr Manmohan Singh, the finance minister, said in an interview
that there was no other way of carrying out change in a large democracy such
as India.
He added that the government's economic policies had been given a stamp of
approval from an International Monetary Fund delegation, which last week
completed a far-reaching review of India's economy and reforms. The IMF
routinely carries out such reviews in countries that receive its support.
The IMF is lending India money under a standby programme designed to help
the country implement reforms to liberalise the economy after decades of
heavy state intervention and regulation.
India is also asking the IMF for an extended fund facility and an enhanced
structural adjustment facility. These are longer-term loan programmes, which
could start at the beginning of the 1993-1994 financial year next April and
run for three years or more.
The terms of these loans have yet to be settled. However, finance ministry
officials believe that the Indian government and the IMF have broadly
similar views of the likely economic targets.
Mr Ahluwalia said that the next substantial announcements about the future
economic reform programme would be contained in the budget for next year,
which will be published in mid-February.
The Indian economy has endured a sharp slowdown in growth since the reforms
were introduced as the government has sought to bring inflation and
difficulties with the balance of payments under control. Mr Ahluwalia
predicted that signs of a strong recovery would emerge in the next few
months, followed by more robust growth in the 1993-1994 financial year.
By the mid-1990s the economy could be expanding at a rate of 6.5 per cent a
year, compared with a likely 3.5 to 4 per cent in the current year.
</TEXT>
