<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / World Trade News: Washington in a corner over trade
sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALL THE formulas concocted, plans rejected, trips taken and words spoken
since the EC and US began battling over oilseeds subsidies in the 1980s have
been to no avail.
In pushing hard and insistently for an EC reduction of its massive
subsidies, the US has now backed itself into a corner with no other route to
take than its unilateral 'withdrawal of concessions' - otherwise known as
sanctions - on Dollars 300m (Pounds 194m) worth of EC white wines, rapeseed
oil and wheat gluten.
Many officials believe that with no other course to follow provoking a real
crisis may be the only way of forcing deeply divided EC countries to work
together to offer a satisfactory compromise.
'We regret that we were forced to take this action,' said Mrs Carla Hills,
the US trade representative. 'For five years the EC has refused to provide
the US what it is clearly owed under international trading rules. The
credibility and effectiveness of the Gatt are at stake here.'
The course the US is following is difficult for the legalistic Mrs Hills.
Since the Uruguay Round got under way, US trade officials have committed
themselves to act under multilateral rules, wherever they apply in trade
disputes, and to work to improve the Gatt dispute settlement process.
The US has acted unilaterally against China - which is not a member of the
Gatt - and on intellectual property rights, which is not covered by trade
rules. But wherever possible, it has sought to negotiate; in fact Mrs Hills
has yet to go beyond the threat of imposing trade sanctions.
In Mrs Hills view, the US has played by the rules, won two panel decisions,
delayed for compensation talks, twice tried to fix a level of damages
through arbitration and been blocked by the EC. And it has embarked on an
exhaustive set of negotiations to find a solution within the proposed
Uruguay Round reform of agriculture trade.
On Wednesday the US asked the Gatt council for authorisation to withdraw
tariff concessions given earlier, in essence asking for permission to impose
sanctions. The EC blocked the request. This left the US without clear rules
to follow. To delay action further, would expose the Gatt as a toothless
tiger and a useless court of final appeals.
All hope of agreement ended, in fact, because of a lack of trust. The US
could not believe in proposed EC formulas for limiting oilseeds production.
With so many economic problems of its own the US felt it could not accept a
fudged accord which did not produce the expected results.
The action came two days after the election, leaving Mrs Hills less than
three months in office. She did not approach President-elect Bill Clinton or
anyone on his staff because, as she explained yesterday, no one had yet been
appointed whom she could consult.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
