<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / World Trade News: Oilseeds row has used up options
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AS FAR as Gatt's formal disputes machinery is concerned, the US-EC oilseeds
dispute has gone as far as it can. Gatt officials acknowledged yesterday
that nothing more could be done within the Gatt framework if the two
partners were not able or prepared to reach a negotiated agreement.
Strictly, in imposing trade sanctions without Gatt authorisation, the US is
violating Gatt procedures which require such decisions to be made by
consensus. The EC, which in effect vetoed that consensus, would be equally
in breach of the rules by retaliating.
However, the US undoubtedly has the better moral argument, since the cause
of its action remains the failure of the Community to comply with earlier
Gatt decisions.
Washington can reasonably claim to have 'gone the extra mile' to resolve the
five-year-old dispute within the multi-lateral system.
In 1989, a Gatt panel ruled that the EC's oilseed subsidy regime impaired
the benefits of duty-free access for oilseeds into the EC granted in a 1962
US-EC deal.
Earlier this year, the same panel ruled that the EC's new subsidy scheme,
changed in response to the first judgment, was no better. The EC refused to
amend the scheme again. Instead, it took the second option proposed by the
panel, offering compensation by way of trade concessions on other items.
These offers proved unacceptable to the US and other oilseeds producers.
In September, the US proposed binding arbitration on the amount of trade
damages involved, put by Washington at Dollars 1.6bn (Pounds 1.03bn) and by
the EC at no more than Dollars 400m. This procedure, unprecedented in Gatt,
was refused by the EC. Subsequent bilateral negotiations on the issue
finally broke down in Chicago earlier this week.
Gatt officials admit the organisation's disputes procedures have been
stretched to the limit in this case, but point out that sanctions do not
solve the problem either.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
