<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Schlesinger doubt on Eurobankers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank president yesterday expressed doubt whether European
countries will be able to provide genuinely independent people to sit on the
council of the planned European Central Bank.
In a speech in Amsterdam highlighting the German central bank's scepticism
about the path to monetary union in Europe, Mr Helmut Schlesinger warned
that central bankers sometimes had to operate without government or public
support if they were to hold to their central goal of curbing inflation.
Worries about the domestic impact of the new bank's policies might stop
suitably qualified central bankers from joining the institution, he said.
He explicitly rejected President Mr Francois Mitterrand's recent comments
that the future European central bankers would be monetary technicians,
answering to EC governments. The Maastricht treaty, which guarantees the
independence of the new institution, had to be implemented 'to the letter',
he said.
New orders for west Germany's manufacturing industry fell by 0.5 per cent in
September from August, the seventh successive monthly decline, Quentin Peel
writes from Bonn.
The drop was entirely accounted for by a 2 per cent fall in export orders,
according to the Economics Ministry. Orders from the home market increased
by 0.5 per cent.
A comparison of the combined total of August and September with the same two
months of 1991 shows an overall drop of 4.7 per cent. Within that total,
export orders were down 6.7 per cent, and domestic orders by just 3.8 per
cent.
Over the year, capital goods orders were down 6.9 per cent.
Germany enjoyed a trade surplus in September of DM5.6bn, with exports of
DM55.6bn against imports of DM50bn. The overall balance of payments was in
deficit to the tune of DM4.2bn.
</TEXT>
