<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Markets sense early realignment in ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE was growing speculation in financial markets yesterday that another
realignment of the European exchange rate mechanism (ERM) will take place
before the end of the year, following a number of statements from European
governments.
Mr Carlos Solchaga, Spain's finance minister, told the New York Times that a
further realignment in the ERM would probably be needed before the end of
the year to restore stability to the system. 'We are absolutely open to all
changes of parities,' he said.
A spokeswoman at the Spanish Finance Ministry said yesterday that Mr
Solchaga's comments dated back to an interview given last month and that the
arguments for a realignment were now much less clear.
However, speculation was boosted later in the day by Ireland's announcement
that it will be lifting all its remaining exchange controls by the end of
this year.
Mr Bertie Ahern, Ireland's finance minister, said: 'We are committed, under
existing European Community agreements, to remove all our remaining exchange
controls by the end of this year. We will of course fully comply with this
obligation.'
Analysts said that the abandonment of exchange controls could accompany a
devaluation of the Irish punt. The currency is one of the weaker ERM
members, but its position in the system would be stabilised by a
devaluation.
</TEXT>
