<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8ABDFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Cabinet agrees spending cuts amid hints of tax concessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CABINET yesterday settled the sweeping cuts in government programmes
needed to meet its spending targets amid Whitehall hints that next week's
Autumn Statement could include a modest package of tax concessions.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, will withhold from the cabinet the details
of his promised economic 'recovery' programme until a few hours before his
speech to the House of Commons next Thursday.
The imposition of Budget-style secrecy strengthened the suspicion of
ministers that the Treasury is considering tax concessions to boost
industrial confidence and prevent a further slump in the housing market.
Mr Lamont's colleagues are convinced that the statement will be followed by
a further cut in interest rates from the present 8 per cent, taking the
level of borrowing costs down to their lowest since the 1970s.
The programme will contain separate incentives for private sector
involvement in large-scale infrastructure projects and may temporarily lift
some of the restrictions which prevent local authorities from spending their
capital receipts. Such creative accounting would push up the level of
borrowing but would keep increased spending outside the Treasury's spending
total.
However, warnings from some members of the cabinet that the Treasury would
reveal what one described as a 'horrendous' increase in public borrowing
tempered expectations of a 'mini-Budget' with wide-ranging tax changes.
They believe that an explosion in borrowing - now expected to total over
Pounds 40bn next year - may force the chancellor to consider an overall tax
increase in next year's Budget, most probably through an extension of VAT.
The government's concern about the potential for renewed unrest on the Tory
backbenches was underlined by a decision by Mr Lamont, and Mr Michael
Portillo, to hold an intensive series of meetings with ministers and MPs.
Every Tory MP outside the cabinet will be invited to the Treasury next week
to receive a briefing on the harsh economic background to the statement.
The cabinet accord yesterday on the cuts in Whitehall programmes needed to
meet the target for next year, will involve an intense squeeze on public
sector pay, with budgets allowing for increases of less than 2 per cent. But
ministers have rejected a pay freeze because of the anticipated political
outcry.
Ministers are nonetheless braced for a series of possible backbench
rebellions over proposed cuts in some social security programmes, a sharp
reduction in the defence budget and an agreement to limit the resources to
smooth next year's introduction of the council tax.
Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, has warned colleagues that
limiting the amount of money available for 'transitional relief' will mean
sharp increases in bills for households in the south.
Among the other casualties of the spending round, Mrs Virginia Bottomley,
health secretary, has lost several hundred million pounds from her budget
and Mrs Gillian Shephard has faced a tight squeeze on the Employment
Department's training budget.
</TEXT>
