<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8AHMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Further aluminium production
cuts urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CUT of another 1m tonnes in western world aluminium production next year
from present levels would push the metal's price up by about 12 cents a lb
to 65 cents, according to Mr Stewart Spector, the New York-based industry
observer and author of the Spector Report.
'This won't make the industry solvent but at least 80 per cent of its
smelters would then be operating at or above their cash costs,' he says.
Mr Spector calculates that, at the present aluminium price of about 53 cents
a lb, more than two-thirds of the smelters outside the former eastern bloc
are operating at a cash loss. Many more are suffering losses on a full-cost
basis.
He suggests the industry can choose its level of prices and profits next
year. But he warns that a production cut of 500,000 tonnes in aluminium
ingot production would take prices only to 56 cents a lb and 'that certainly
won't result in higher (aluminium company) profits in 1993'.
In the second half of 1991 western aluminium producers implemented permanent
closures and temporary cuts totalling 850,000 tonnes in a full year. But
demand remained flat, imports from the Commonwealth of Independent States
continued to flood in and aluminium stocks in London Metal Exchange
warehouses are now 1m tonnes higher than in June 1991 when the first
capacity cuts were implemented.
So why is the industry continuing to increase production rather than make
cuts?
Mr Geoff Campbell, analyst at Ord Minnett, part of the Westpac banking
group, points to the aluminium industry's version of Catch 22. Shutting down
part of a smelter usually pushes unit costs up. Closing a complete smelter
can frequently cause problems because many of the industry's big producers
are integrated groups. They have downstream facilities to supply or upstream
refineries supplying them with alumina (aluminium oxide). So the closure of
a high-cost smelter may cause more problems than it solves. He concludes:
'The only realistic justification for reducing output is to get the
aluminium price up and there is not much point closing down an operation
because you won't be around to take advantage of the subsequent price rise'.
And anti-trust legislation prevents producers getting together to organise
between themselves an orderly shutdown of capacity.
Mr Angus MacMillan, research manager at Billiton-Enthoven Metals, the Royal
Dutch/Shell offshoot, suggests: 'The onus is largely, although not
exclusively, on the European producers to reduce output and return the
market to balance'.
He points out aluminium companies have been reluctant to act so far because
of forecasts - up to the summer at least - that an economic recovery was not
far away. 'The temptation to hold on in the hope that better times are just
around the corner is overwhelming when the costs incurred in permanently
closing or mothballing capacity are taken into account.'
Mr MacMillan says that producers also had the chance to sell metal forward
at higher prices earlier this year and protect themselves from the present
environment to some extent.
He says the market is full of rumours about more capacity cuts but 'even if
they materialise, there is a real danger that we will experience a repeat of
the second half of last year, when successive announcements about cuts were
regarded as too little too late and prices continued to slide.'
</TEXT>
