<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Last minute Chinese bid wins
Peruvian iron company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHIUGANG Corporation from the People's Republic of China became the new
owner of Peru's state iron producer yesterday in Lima. The investment,
totalling USDollars 311.8m, is the first made by communist China in Latin
America, according to Shougang directors.
Shougang amply exceeded the minimum bidding requirement set by Copri, Peru's
state privatisation commission. The Chinese offer for 100 per cent of Hierro
Peru's shares was Dollars 120m compared with a minimum of Dollars 22m; and
it has pledged to invest a further Dollars 150m over the next three years in
much-needed modernisation of equipment (The minimum investment commitment
was set at Dollars 60m). In addition, Shougang must assume Hierro Peru's
debts, projected at Dollars 41.8m.
Front runner for months in the Hierro Peru stakes had been a multinational
consortium of Swiss, Chilean, Mexican and Japanese capital, headed by
Santiago-based Compania Minera del Pacifico and led by former Peruvian mines
minister Mr Pedro-Pablo Kuczynski. Disappointed representatives at
yesterday's auction admitted, however, that the Chinese offer was
unbeatable.
Shougang is one of communist China's 30 top corporations and is in the
mainstream of the country's economic reform. It is described as an
'autonomous state company' with extensive steel, mining and shipping
interests in China and Asia, and turned in profits of Dollars 500m last
year. It plans to double its current steel output over the next seven years.
To maximise the lucrative freight side of the business, Shougang would ship
coal from China to substitute the oil at present used to fire Hierro Peru's
furnaces.
Mr Julio Orihuela, Shougang's Lima representative, said the offer for Hierro
Peru also included construction of a steel mill locally.
</TEXT>
