<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Technology threatens sows with
baby boom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of piglets reared by a single sow every year will rise from an
average of 21 to 30 by the year 2012, using only existing technology, an
international conference on pig breeding was told this week.
Much higher figures could be achieved through improvements in genetic
engineering and reproductive technology, according to Mr Hein van der Steen,
technical manager at the Oxfordshire based Pig Improvement Company. He
suggested a figure of 44.6 piglets per sow.
While such high numbers are still science fiction, 'few of us doubt that
they could be achieved', said Mr van der Steen. He pointed out that the most
efficient breeders were already getting 28 piglets per sow.
The biggest strides were being made in the field of reproductive technology.
Future developments could include the sexing of semen, enabling litters of
only one sex to be produced; in vitro fertilisation; collection and
maturation of eggs; and non-surgical embryo transfers, Mr van der Steen
suggested.
He was doubtful, however, that the public would accept some methods of
increasing efficiency, pointing out that public pressure had already stopped
the use of bovine growth hormone to boost milk production in the European
Community.
'You have to ask: is 45 pigs a year on a sow acceptable from an animal
welfare point of view?' he said. 'We have to find the right balance.'
PIC, which is owned by Dalgety, staged the conference to celebrate the 30th
anniversary of its foundation by a small group of Oxford farmers. It now
boasts sales of Pounds 100m a year, with more than 25 per cent of the UK
market for breeding gilts and a network of worldwide outlets. Last year more
than 750,000 breeding animals were sold in 29 countries.
Mr Richard Clothier, chief executive, said the world market still had plenty
of potential. The US had been slow to develop improved pig breeding, but
demand now far exceeded the ability of breeders to supply. China, another
huge potential market, has not yet started to improve its pig farming.
'Over the next 10 years the demand for breeding stock will at the very least
double - and probably treble,' he said.
</TEXT>
