<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Asarco expects 2.9% copper
demand rise next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PHOENIX, ARIZONA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHAIRMAN of North America's third-largest integrated copper producer
told analysts this week that he expects world copper consumption to increase
to 10.3m tonnes in 1993, a 2.9 per cent advance over this year.
That rise in consumption, and a slower advance in 1993 worldwide production,
should put copper demand about 100,000 tons above output, reversing the
stock build-up that occured in 1992.
Mr Richard Osborne, Chairman of Asarco, based the rosy projections on
assumptions that the economies of Japan and Europe would rebound sharply in
the second half of 1993. He put the rate of consumption growth in the US at
about 1.5 per cent, in Europe at 1 per cent, in Japan at 4.5 per cent and in
the rest of Asia at 7.5 per cent. He forecast China's 1993 imports at
190,000 tonnes, compared with estimates of 165,000 for this year.
Mine expansion in the US, Chile, and Indonesia will boost copper supplies by
2.2 per cent to 9.7m tonnes in 1992, he said, and by 2.6 per cent to 9.9m
tonnes in 1993.
Reporting the company's third quarter results at a meeting in Phoenix,
Arizona, Mr Osborne said Asarco would be delivering an average of 175m lb of
copper to the market in each quarter of 1993. That reflected full production
at the company's Mission and Ray copper mines.
Asarco spent Dollars 350m on expansions and improvements at those
facilities, which were completed between September 1991 and March 1992.
These transformed the company from a metals processor to a fully-integrated
copper producer.
</TEXT>
