<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Douglas Yearley, Phelps Dodge
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DOUGLAS Yearley, chairman of Phelps Dodge, was misreported in the article
'Copper mining projects attract big spenders' on October 28. His comments
were made at a private meeting for analysts to which the press was not
invited.
He did not say at that meeting that the price paid for the Zaldivar copper
project in Chile could be justified only if the copper price stayed at
Dollars 1.15 a lb for the long term. He did not say that the Collahausi
project, also in Chile, was 'on the wrong side of the Andes mountains' and
accordingly could not use a slurry pipeline to transport ore.
Mr Yearley points out that the Lisheen deposit in Ireland is a zinc, not a
copper deposit. He also says that, while he used the word 'amateurs' when
questioned about some international gold mining companies which were moving
into base metals, the word was used in a joking manner. Furthermore, he
described his own company as an 'amateur' in the gold business when compared
with other, more substantial, gold producers.
Mr Yearly says: 'I certainly would not deprecate any of the mineral
properties mentioned in the article. They are all excellent deposits and our
company would be delighted to own an interest in any of them. I was simply
making the point that Phelps Dodge believes it will get a better return for
its money if it invests in exploration rather than purchasing interests in
known deposits, given the prices or recent, publicly announced,
transactions'.
