<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8AHCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Survey of Ireland (9): Irish mice still smile - Electronics
remain healthy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGELA LONG
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
1992 HAS not been a good year for the electronics industry in Ireland -
until recently the great white hope of the country's industrial development
authority.
Ireland's computer industry flashed into life in the 1960s. It meant very
little in terms of jobs and exports until the 1980s; even in 1970 it
generated only 6 per cent of Irish industrial exports. And then, from 7 per
cent at the beginning of the 1980s, computer goods made up 25 per cent of
exports by 1991, and software accounted for 7 per cent - out of nowhere a
mere decade earlier. The proud (if esoteric) boast was that Ireland was
responsible for 90 per cent of the mice in Europe.
Electronics generally had been following the same trend. By last year there
were 300 companies set up in Ireland, employing over 28,000 people,
exporting goods worth IPounds 4bn.
So far hundreds of jobs have been lost at the plants of foreign
multinationals, which had been identified as great providers of jobs,
service jobs and export dollars. The first bad news came in May, when Apple
Computer indicated that 400 jobs would go at its European headquarters in
Cork. Fortunately for the workforce, Apple later modified its decision, and
no jobs have gone yet. But the company had been looking in the direction of
the far east (anathema to the Irish government and trade unions) where it
plans to centralise its printed circuit board (PCB) manufacture.
Also in May, BG Turnkey, a supplier to computer manufacturers, laid off 30
staff. In July Digital announced that it wanted 100 voluntary redundancies
from its Galway plant (a Digital operation at Clonmel closed in May 1991),
and if these were not forthcoming it would have to impose redundancy.
Then came August, a wicked month indeed. Pulse, an American electronics
firm, sacked 125; then Wang announced that 100 jobs would have to go at its
Dollars 75m plant in Limerick. The other big job losses announced in August
were also at American companies; the US has the highest foreign
representation in Ireland, with about 350 plants or offices out of 1,000.
The Wang announcement had the biggest impact, partly because it came in the
same week as publication of another 500 redundancies effective at foreign
multinationals operations concentrated in the west of Ireland. The bad news
gave ammunition to those who had criticised the government and the
Industrial Development Authority (IDA) for heavy reliance on foreign
companies to create jobs and capital by setting up operations in Ireland.
Mr Pat Rabbitte, spokesman on commerce and industry for the vocal minority
party, the Democratic Left, says: 'The experience with Wang illustrates all
the problems associated with relying so heavily on multinationals for job
creation. The excellent record of Wang's Irish operation was not enough to
save them.' This is the rub: having one's destiny controlled from afar. In
the Irish context this is especially irritating; it is at once a fact of
history and of the economic present.
But it is not time to lower the curtain on this contemporary success story
for Irish industry.
The IDA says it has no plans for a U-turn away from its strategy of chasing
electronics companies with generous financial inducements and the lure of a
skilled English-speaking workforce. And there have also been a number of
positive events in 1992.
Wang is a typical case from the computer sector. It came in 1980 when times
were good, speaking of a possible 1,500 jobs in the Limerick plant. But the
actual figure never exceeded 700, although the people of Limerick were
delighted with the contribution the company made to the area. In recent
years turnover hovered around the IPounds 300m.
But the Wang dream turned sour. US head office said that the total
workforce, 12,000 internationally, would have to shrink to 5,000. The world
recession was taking its toll, and the advantages of cheaper manufacture in
the Far East could not be ignored by hard-pressed computer companies.
Additions to the sector, such as a new plant in Coolock, Co Dublin, to be
built by US firm Seagate Technologies, and a takeover of the Nixdorf plant
in Wicklow by Maxtor, are in doubt; both companies have suspended decisions.
(Together, these ventures would have created over 2,500 jobs  - jobs sorely
needed in the context of 21 per cent unemployment nationally.) But companies
like Motorola and Intel are still filing good results. Dell, another
American computer company based in Limerick, reported a 129 per cent
increase in sales during the quarter ended August 1992 - and net income up
77 per cent.
The list of electronics companies attracted by lreland's generous provisions
for foreign investors is long and star-studded: NEC, Amdahl, Microsoft,
Siemens, Phillips Ericcson, Claris. Not all of them are in bad straits,
although in the middle of a severe international recession there is not much
reckless spending.
Lay-offs must be seen in the context of the world recession, says Martin
Cronin, manager of the electronics division at the IDA. 'Workers have been
laid off in the UK and the US. Compared with the worldwide situation,
Ireland is still in a strong position. And the response of the electronic
industry worldwide would be similar to Ireland's. It's a technology that is
evolving very rapidly, and new products will come in bursts.'
The National Microelectronics Centre at the Plassey Technology park is
engaged in doing 'cutting-edge' research, and the nearby making the
graduates with skills the electronics companies need.
Mr Albert Reynolds, the Taoiseach, acknowledged the changing scene last
month: 'While previously we had been able to rely on an attractive package
of fiscal incentives . . this is increasingly being matched by our
competitors in other countries. It is therefore essential that Ireland
should develop additional sources of advantage.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
