<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8AG8FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Survey of Ireland (3): Undeterred by recession - 'A
successful unemployed economy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE Irish economy can be considered both a success and a failure
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
depending on your viewpoint. Low inflation, sustained growth and a healthy
trade surplus add up to a classic textbook case of good economic management.
The appendix would have to point out, though, that almost a quarter of the
3.5m population is marginalised from the mainstream economy, and a
substantial proportion more has little to show for that good economic
management.
In Dublin, the carefully-tended gardens of the middle- and upper-class
neighbourhoods of the 'southside' - south of the river Liffey, which bisects
the city - give an aura of genteel prosperity. The only hint of anxiety is
the ubiquitous burglar alarm, now to be seen on almost any house with a
reasonable coat of paint. (It could probably rate alongside the personal
computer as a yardstick of the occupant's standard-of-living.) City centre
restaurants, with their uniformly expensive menus, seem invariably to be
full, and doing a thriving business.
On the other side of the Liffey on the 'northside' where lower-middle class
and working class neighbourhoods predominate, the pubs, supermarkets and
fast-food shops continue to ring up profits, but their trade is increasingly
being financed by transfers from the exchequer in the form of welfare and
unemployment benefits.
Despite the recession, Ireland continues to have one of the fastest-growing
economies in the European Community, averaging 5 per cent growth per annum
over the past five years. But it also has the longest dole queues; grown
longer by 30 per cent over the past two years. By the end of 1992
unemployment is projected to pass 300,000, over 21 per cent of the labour
force; easily the highest in the EC.
This has prompted one sarcastic commentator to remark that Ireland has 'one
of the most successful unemployed economies in the world.' Two things
explain this ambiguity: Ireland's demographic trends, and its membership of
the narrow band of the exchange rate mechanism (ERM) within the EC.
Although the birth rate has fallen to about 50,000 live births per annum,
from 70,000 10 years ago, there will be no significant reduction in the
number of people entering the labour market until the end of the decade.
Emigration, the traditional escape valve for those unable to find work in
Ireland, has declined from an average 30,000 per year in the late 1980s to
only 1,000 last year - because of recession in the UK and the US.
Meanwhile the government's policy to maintain a strong punt within the ERM
has severely restricted exchequer freedom to borrow and spend. This has had
a deflationary effect on employment and domestic demand, but has created a
stable macro-economic environment, attractive to export-orientated inward
investment. It is that sector which has shown the most dramatic growth in
recent years.
Merchandise exports are expected to be up by 10 per cent this year, while
manufacturing output is predicted to grow by 7 per cent. This impressive
performance is now under threat.
In September sterling abandoned the ERM and floated downwards. Some 32 per
cent of Irish exports are destined for the UK; about 42 percent of imports
are sourced there. The financial markets, having overwhelmed sterling,
turned on the punt, anticipating that the government would be forced into a
devaluation.
The government, however, has held firm. Using its remnant exchange controls
(which are scheduled to be abolished by the end of the year), raising
interest rates by 3 percentage points, and borrowing abroad to rebuild
reserves lost in defending the punt in the first speculative rush in
September, it has managed to throw together a credible defence of the punt.
Upon this the entire edifice of Ireland's economic policy is structured.
Maintaining the punt's link to the DM is Ireland's passport to the
'inner-core' of hard-currency EC states, which may press ahead with plans
for monetary union and a single currency if a two-speed EC eventually
emerges out of the ERM crisis. There is almost unanimous agreement across
Irish political party lines, and between employers' organisations and trade
unions, that to link the fate of the Irish economy to that of sterling and
the UK's ailing economy would be a fatal error.
The question is whether the very high real interest rates now being suffered
by the economy, currently in excess of 11 per cent, will prove more damaging
than sterling's devaluation. Mr Bertie Ahern, the Irish finance minister
says: 'The real level of interest rate is far too high, and for the
performance of the economy is almost ridiculous . . .if the Germans move (to
lower rates) this side of Christmas, it will allow us to do so as well, but
we will have to live with high interest rates certainly for this quarter.
(Then) in 1993 we would be trying to roll back that 3 per cent increase.'
Mr John Bruton, leader of Fine Gael, the opposition party, accuses the
government of having 'a foreign exchange policy but not an economic policy'.
He is arguing for thorough structural reforms in the economy - a sweeping
reform of the tax legislation which currently encourages capital-intensive
investment but discourages labour-intensive investment. High national
insurance contributions should be reduced and income tax bands widened to
encourage investment and job creation, he says.
Mr Ahern has a worried eye on next year's budget. This year the target of an
exchequer borrowing requirement of IPounds 590m, or 2.4 per cent, looks
likely to be met. Next year a 9 per cent rise in the public sector wage bill
is already locked in through outstanding agreements with the unions. This
leaves stark choices: either to abandon the convergence criteria for EC
monetary union, or implement significant spending cuts in public services.
With a general election looming, neither one of these is a politically soft
option.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 34
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9351</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8AG6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Survey of Ireland (2): Cork is fighting back / A look at the
second city
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DES O'SULLIVAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN the Culliton review group on industrial policy looked at Irish ports it
found serious problems, expressed concern about competitiveness and
recommended action. But the group bypassed Cork altogether - although the
republic's second city has Ireland's most successful port.
Complaints about being ignored are often dismissed as typical of the 'second
city' syndrome. Yet the proposed designation of Cork as a Europort is a
political football which has been kicked around fruitlessly for years. Just
as there is an urgent need to improve the Cork-Dublin road, so there is a
priority need, too, to improve the route from Dublin to Rosslare, Cork's
competitor port.
The view that Cork loses out to centralised decision-making in Dublin
(particularly during the years when Charles Haughey led the Irish
government) is widespread. Father Donal Linehan, parish priest of Mayfield,
on Cork's poorer north side, is alarmed about large concentrations of people
outside the labour force, and believes that for over 20 years the north side
in particular has not benefited from national growth.
Cork has lost its traditional industry base over the past 10 years. It is
fighting back by capitalising on natural advantages such as Cork harbour,
and the availability of a technically advanced and skilled young labour
force. The Cork economy is heavily influenced by agriculture, but the 10 per
cent increase in farm incomes this year is not matched by hopes of important
expansion in 1993. This year the harvest was poor.
High interest rates have brought widespread uncertainty, and consumers are
not spending. 'A lot of people are just being very cautious,' observes
George Mansfield, Allied Irish Bank's regional manager. 'But there have been
quite a number of property deals, indicating confidence in the future.'
Unemployment - intractable even in the good years - remains the big problem.
The urgent need to deliver jobs fuelled local suspicions that chemical
industries looking for new locations were pushing against an open door.
Environmentalists lined up against industrialists during long public
planning inquiries into a Merrell Dow proposal to build a factory on a
greenfield site in east Cork, and the Sandoz plan to invest in Ireland's
most expensive chemical plant at Ringaskiddy.
Merrell Dow retains its planning permission but decided not to proceed. The
Sandoz fire at Basle in 1986, which created an environmental disaster on the
Rhine, contributed to an enormous negative public response when the Cork
plant was first mooted. Sandoz mentioned Puerto Rico as an alternative
location. Eventually planning permission was granted under conditions as
rigorous as in Germany or Switzerland.
Sandoz received 5,000 job applications on the basis of a plan which, if
implemented, will ultimately employ 400 people. One advertisement for 40
operatives drew 1,800 applications. Sandoz is a company which the Cork
Environmental Alliance (CEA) - which operates entirely on public support,
with just one full-time staffer - continues to view with deep suspicion.
Yet even here there is a sensitivity about the lack of jobs. 'We would like
to see Ireland move in the direction of more jobs because of our
environment, not in spite of it,' says Geraldine O'Brien of the CEA. 'We are
not satisfied with the standards. Factories are not meant to produce smells.
When they do the rate of prosecution is laughable - and the fines imposed
are peanuts.'
There is a shortage of research and information on the challenges to human
health and the environment posed by the chemical industry in the Cork
harbour area. 'We have laws and they are not enforced,' Ms O'Brien
complains.
Seven of the world's top 15 pharmaceutical companies now have operations
centred in Cork or Munster. Most of these plants produce bulk chemicals for
export (valued in 1991 at IrPounds 750-IrPounds 800m).
Mr Neil Buckley, director-general of the Federation of Irish Chemical
Industries, points out that while the industry was establishing itself not
one company closed down. 'The overall net picture is one of consistent
growth in output and employment.'
Other important newcomers are the computer and electronics industries. Apple
Computers has its European manufacturing base in Cork. With over 1,000
people on the payroll, it is now the city's largest employer.
There were shockwaves this year when Apple suggested that it might move
printed circuit board manufacture to the far east. Cork's advantages in
terms of just-in-time delivery and flexibility in manufacturing in a variety
of languages averted the risk.
The long-awaited decentralisation of the Central Statistics Office from
Dublin to Cork, scheduled for next year, will be a significant move locally.
The Industrial Development Authority (IDA) is anticipating the arrival of a
Taiwanese electronics park at Ringaskiddy. Taiwan does not yet have a
foothold in Europe, so this is a pioneering proposal. There was a hold-up in
the granting of planning permission because of one objector, but this has
now been resolved.
The Gulf war reduced the number of visits from industrialists last year and,
according to Barry Condron, the IDA regional director, its effects are still
being felt. Visits undertaken by companies seeking a base in Europe show an
increase this year, but decisions are likely to be delayed until there is an
improvement in the market.
Cork port benefited from strike problems at Dublin, but it has proved that
it can attract shippers on its own merits. Free of industrial strife for the
past 10 years, important rationalisation and investment programmes have made
the port competitive and efficient. In the first nine months of this year,
shipments topped 4.88m tonnes. Port authorities confidently expect a
record-breaking 6.5m tonnes by the end of 1992.
Brittany Ferries and Irish Ferries will each increase sailings next year,
with services to Roskoff, St Malo, Cherbourg and Le Havre. This reflects the
fact that more and more Europeans view Cork as the gateway to the west of
Ireland - and road networks to the west are improving fast. Services will
continue to improve, and in the next five years Cork port is planning
investments in 12 projects worth over IrPounds 50m.
</TEXT>
