<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Call to snub Argentine strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARGENTINA'S government yesterday stepped up pressure on workers to ignore a
general strike called for Monday by the CGT trade union confederation. It
took out full-page newspaper advertisements saying: 'The country is
advancing. The November 9 general strike is a step back.'
Recognising the right to strike, the government demanded the unions also
recognise the 'rights of the rest of the population'.
The governing Peronist party, which has close links to the union movement,
said the strike had 'ulterior political ends'. President Carlos Menem
promised to ensure basic services such as health, transport, energy and
banking services.
Previous threats by the weak and divided unions to call a general strike
have failed in the face of a determined and aggressive government that has
systematically eroded their privileges. The most hated of the government's
measures is a decree linking wage rises to productivity increases, rather
than inflation. The inflation rate now stands at 20 per cent a year, while
wage increases trail far behind.
However, falling real wages and government attempts to reform rigid labour
laws and wrest some Dollars 5bn in welfare funds from the union leadership
have galvanised them into organising the first general strike against Mr
Menem's government, after staging 13 stoppages against the previous Radical
government of Raul Alfonsn.
Nonetheless, Mr Domingo Cavallo, economy minister, is determined to force
labour legislation through Congress, to improve industry's international
competitiveness. Economists say Congress must approve the reforms by early
1993.
</TEXT>
