<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INCREASINGLY hostile battle for control of Harmony Leisure, the
loss-making pubs and restaurants group, reached a a new pitch yesterday when
rebel shareholders accused the board of financial incompetence and
defamatory tactics.
Launching their strategy to revive the company, the dissidents said they
would reverse the slide in Harmony's performance marked by accumulated
losses of Pounds 6.9m over the past three years.
Mr Andrew Martyr, leader of the rebel group, dismissed management
allegations that the dissidents had misled shareholders about their former
directorships and lack of experience.
Harmony was behaving like President Bush's failed campaign team and 'the
board has resorted to personal attacks and innuendo to stave off defeat,' he
said.
The rebel leaders, who hope to oust the board at an extraordinary meeting
later this month, claim 36 per cent support for their restructuring plans.
The board has rejected the rebel plans as 'opportunistic' and urged
shareholders to back the current management team.
Mr Martyr, however, warned that failure to unseat the board could result in
Harmony being absorbed by a larger group, leaving shareholders facing
considerable losses.
'The board has proved itself incapable of taking the action necessary to
rescue Harmony,' he said.
