FT  06 NOV 92 / International Company News: Amcoal holds dividend despite
first-half reverse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LOWER sales and an adverse tax adjustment contributed to a fall in
first-half attributable earnings of 15 per cent at Amcoal, South Africa's
largest coal group and the coal arm of the Anglo American Corporation.
But the dividend was maintained at 150 cents a share, despite the fall in
per-share earnings to 537 cents from 632 cents.
Sales of coal and coke fell by 2 per cent to 20.74m tonnes from 21.2m
tonnes. Export sales were 9 per cent higher at 5.16m tonnes compared with
4.74m tonnes, but sales in the domestic market were lower.
Export profitability was lower as weaker dollar prices offset the benefits
of increased volumes and a weaker rand/dollar exchange rate, while colliery
working costs were kept below the inflation rate.
Operating profits fell by 6.6 per cent to R202.7m (Dollars 69.8m) from
R217m, although turnover rose to R952.7m from R948.9m. Attributable earnings
emerged at R135.2m compared with R159m. This resulted from lower interest
and investment income - a function of higher capital expenditure and lower
interest rates - and a fall in the favourable adjustment to the previous
year's deferred tax benefits, arising from a lower rate of tax.
Mr David Rankin, chairman, said Amcoal's operations were likely to remain at
the same level in the second half despite the weak domestic economy.
He said the combination of increased volumes and the rand/dollar exchange
rate should ensure second-half earnings similar to those just reported.
</TEXT>
