<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / UK Company News: Wm Low picks up in second half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WM LOW, the Dundee-based food retailer, yesterday reported a 12.5 per cent
fall in profits, but said problems which led to a poor first half had been
overcome.
Pre-tax profits fell from Pounds 23.6m to Pounds 20.6m in the year to
September 5. Most of the decline came in the first half, when profits fell
23 per cent to Pounds 8.82m, because of falling margins and one-off costs.
Mr James Millar, chairman, said: 'This has been a game of two halves. The
first half was a one-off and we've got it out of the system'.
Operating margins, which fell to 3.98 per cent in the first half, partly
because of increased promotional sending, recovered to 5.93 per cent, only
slightly below the comparative period figure of 6.1 per cent.
Turnover increased 9.4 per cent to Pounds 420.1m, mainly due to new store
openings. Five new stores were opened while three neighbourhood branches
were closed, leading to a net gain of 90,000 sq ft. Like-for-like sales
increased 2.7 per cent, about half of which came from inflation.
Depreciation was Pounds 7.8m with capital expenditure - mainly on new stores
 -unchanged at Pounds 44.3m. The expansion programme pushed up net
borrowings to Pounds 37.9m (Pounds 11.3m) with gearing at 24.8 per cent.
A lower than expected tax charge of 17 per cent, due to the release of
unnecessary provisions, could not prevent a fall in fully diluted earnings
per share to 24.92p (27.9p).
The company proposes an unchanged final dividend of 5.7p, to give a
maintained total of 8.4p.
Mr Colin Mitchell, the former managing director who left abruptly in
February, received severance pay of Pounds 223,000. The company said Mr
Philip Spicer, presently national food manager with Co-operative Retail
Services, had been appointed chief executive.
COMMENT
Wm Low's shares gained 15p to 239p yesterday and have now recovered much of
the ground lost following the poor interims. Margins have been restored and
new stores appear to be performing well. But despite the assurance of Mr
Millar's footballing analogy, retailing is a funny old game and Wm Low's
sceptics are still not convinced. Some point to the company's erratic profit
record, and others question whether it can really survive a dual assault on
its Scottish heartland by majors like Sainsbury and discounters like
Shoprite. Forecast profits of Pounds 23m put the shares on just under 9
times, which looks cheap relative to the sector. The shares may go higher,
but long-established reasons for the company's low rating - its size and
store portfolio - are still valid.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-9376</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKFB8AEWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921106
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / UK Company News: US halts production of Tate's sweetener
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES FOR Sucralose, a calorie-free sweetener developed by Tate &amp; Lyle, have
been further deflated by news that production has been halted in the US,
pending regulatory approval.
The US is estimated to account for 85 per cent of the Dollars 1bn (Pounds
600m) a year world market for high intensity sweeteners, led by NutraSweet
from Monsanto, the US chemicals group.
But although Tate and its US partner Johnson &amp; Johnson have spent Pounds
150m in more than 15 years of development, the product is so far only on
sale in Canada, where it gained approval a year ago.
As stocks have piled high enough to satisfy Canadian demand 'for the
foreseeable future' - which one analyst calculated to be four years - two US
plants have been mothballed by J&amp;J. The product is described as 'highly
stable' and so is not expected to go stale.
J&amp;J submitted an application to the US Food and Drugs Administration in
February 1987. The FDA would only say yesterday that the petition was still
under review.
J&amp;J said the length of time taken was 'not really unusual.' Aspartame, the
NutraSweet ingredient, took 10 years.
UK analysts were not expecting Sucralose to contribute yet to Tate's
profits. But some recently downgraded estimates for the year just ended by
about Pounds 8m, to less than Pounds 190m pre-tax, to allow for the
write-off of previously capitalised development spending.
Mr Mark Lynch, at SG Warburg, said the delay in gaining FDA approval did
cause concern in terms of Tate's medium-term earnings prospects.
One analyst said there had been a time when it seemed Sucralose and the fat
substitute Stellar, launched last year, might become star products, like the
blockbuster drugs that help the ratings of pharmaceutical companies.
However, they now seemed insignificant alongside the factors affecting the
main sugar businesses.
</TEXT>
