<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Bernie Cornfeld joins bid for MGM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR BERNIE CORNFELD, the controversial American mutual funds promoter whose
empire collapsed more than 20 years ago, is hoping to make a comeback today
when he joins in a Dollars 500m (Pounds 324m) cash bid for Hollywood's MGM
film studio.
The 65-year-old Mr Cornfeld said he was joining forces for the bid with Mr
Giovanni Di Stefano, a former business associate of Mr Giancarlo Parretti,
the Italian former owner of MGM.
Mr Di Stefano is locked in several legal battles with Credit Lyonnais, the
French state bank that suffered embarrassment last year when it was revealed
to have loaned Mr Parretti Dollars 1bn for his successful 1990 MGM bid.
The French bank then forced Mr Parretti out of MGM in a US court and last
spring took possession of the once great studio, which is believed to be
making heavy losses.
Mr Di Stefano, who once spent three years in prison in the UK after being
convicted of fraudulent trading, said the Dollars 500m bid would be made
today to the Netherlands branch of Credit Lyonnais.
The proposed takeover vehicle will be a Luxembourg-registered company called
The Lion Group SA, which is more than 50 per cent controlled by Mr Di
Stefano and has, as a minority shareholder, a company controlled by Mr
Cornfeld. The bidders claim to have half the Dollars 500m in cash and the
rest in loans from Italian and German banks.
Mr Cornfeld spent 11 months in a Swiss jail in 1973 accused of fraud in
connection with his Investors Overseas Services (IOS) business. He was
acquitted of the charges in 1979.
Mr Di Stefano said he spoke last week to a senior executive of Credit
Lyonnais and was told 'to come back when the money is lined up'.
But Credit Lyonnais said: 'There has been absolutely no contact with Mr
Cornfeld and Mr Di Stefano. Their statements are unworthy of any comment by
us.'
Mr Cornfeld said he was excited at the prospect of attempting his first
high-profile transaction in 20 years and he and Mr Di Stefano planned to
name themselves as co-chairmen of MGM if the bid succeeds.
'I see this as an opportunity to turn around a major company in the film
business. I'll be active in management,' he said.
</TEXT>
