<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / Defeated Irish government faces election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRELAND is to hold a general election in three weeks, following the defeat
of the government on a confidence motion yesterday.
The opposition parties were joined by the Progressive Democrats (PDs), who
had withdrawn from the coalition on Wednesday evening, in voting against the
government on the motion, resulting in its defeat by 88 votes to 77. The
election date will be November 25. An abortion referendum originally
scheduled for December 3 will now be held on the same day.
In yesterday's debate on the confidence motion, unemployment, the recession,
taxation, Northern Ireland and public probity were signalled as issues that
will dominate what will be a brief but intense electoral campaign.
In the first clashes of the campaign, the prime minister, Mr Albert
Reynolds, accused the PDs of undermining his government. He said:
'Coalitions where the junior partner holds the senior one to ransom do not
work with the same cohesion and effectiveness (as single-party
governments).' He claimed that the opposition parties would be unable to
form a stable government and said: 'I believe that single-party, Fianna Fail
government under my leadership can do far more for this country that a
chaotic motley coalition led by deputy Bruton.' Mr John Bruton, the leader
of the main opposition party, Fine Gael, accused Mr Reynolds' party of
having been 'a glitzy soap opera' while in government.
Mr Des O'Malley, the PD leader who was at the centre of the recent coalition
crisis, said he regretted his decision to abandon the coalition, but added:
'The need to give this country the opportunity to choose an effective
government must come first.'
Mr Dick Spring, leader of the Labour party, which may hold the balance of
power in a hung parliament after the election, warned that in any new
coalition 'there will have to be fundamental changes in the present set of
policies on offer from (Fianna Fail and Fine Gael), and a fundamental
commitment to a much higher level of integrity than has been evident up to
now'. His party intends to wage 'an all-out attack on unemployment' which
would be accompanied by 'a judicious and carefully planned increase in our
borrowing capacity' he said.
See Irish survey
