<HEADLINE>
FT  06 NOV 92 / International Company News: Thomson family sells 40% stake
in Hudbay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FAMILY of Lord Thomson of Fleet has sold the bulk of its controlling
interest in Hudson's Bay Company, Canada's biggest department store group
and North America's oldest public company.
Woodbridge, the Thomsons' holding company, said yesterday that it has raised
CDollars 545m (USDollars 439.5m) through the sale to a group of underwriters
of 20m Hudson's Bay shares. The stock will be distributed to investors at a
price of CDollars 27.25 a share, to be paid in two instalments over the next
year.
The sale cuts Woodbridge's stake in HBC from 65 per cent to 25 per cent. The
Thomsons will remain HBC's largest single shareholder for the time being.
They have agreed not to sell their remaining interest for at least a year
without the underwriters' consent.
Woodbridge said the initiative for the sale had come from the underwriting
group and 'senior management decided the price was right'.
The funds will be used to cut debt and augment working capital. Some of the
proceeds will be available for unidentified future investment, though these
are unlikely to be in the retail field.
The present Lord Thomson of Fleet, who prefers to be known simply as Mr Ken
Thomson, is the son of the former proprietor of The Times of London. With
the help of a group of low-profile managers, he has diversified the family
business, which now includes controlling stakes in Thomson Corporation, the
media and travel group, and Markborough Properties, a North American
property company, as well as the stake in Hudson Bay, originally acquired in
1980.
HBC has a colourful history stretching back more than three centuries, when
it was set up by King Charles II as a fur trading enterprise. It now
controls three groups of department stores with revenues last year of just
over CDollars 5bn. But it has had a spotty earnings record, suffering a
CDollars 4.5m loss in the three months to April.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 31
</PAGE>
</DOC>
